VALUES ('f5000008-0000-0000-0000-000000000008', 8, 'Photogrammetry, GIS and Construction', 'Map the world and stake it out: photo scale, ground sample distance, relief displacement, flying height and stereo parallax; remote sensing, LiDAR and UAS; mapping fundamentals, GIS data models, projections and datums; and construction surveying — stakeout, grades, and earthwork — all tied to the NCEES FS Reference Handbook photogrammetry and earthwork formulas.', 'Weeks 14-15', 12, ARRAY['Vertical photo scale S = f/(H − h) and average scale','Ground sample distance (GSD) from pixel size, flying height, focal length','Relief (radial) displacement d = r·h/H','Flying height, overlap/sidelap, stereo base, and parallax','Remote sensing, multispectral imagery, LiDAR, and UAS/drone mapping','Mapping concepts: scale, contours, vector vs. raster data models','GIS: projections, coordinate systems, datums (NAD83/NAVD88), metadata','Map projections — Lambert vs. Transverse Mercator; geoid vs. ellipsoid','Construction stakeout: offsets, cut/fill, grade, and slope','Earthwork volumes by average end area and the prismoidal formula']::text[], '[{"name":"Vertical photo scale","formula":"S = f / (H − h)"},{"name":"Photo scale (distance ratio)","formula":"S = (photo distance) / (ground distance)"},{"name":"Ground distance from photo","formula":"D_ground = d_photo / S = d_photo · (H − h)/f"},{"name":"Ground sample distance","formula":"GSD = (pixel_size · H) / f"},{"name":"GSD (cm) shortcut","formula":"GSD_cm = (pixel_µm · H_m) / (f_mm · 10)"},{"name":"Relief displacement","formula":"d = r·h / H"},{"name":"Flying height above ground","formula":"H − h = f / S"},{"name":"Stereo base (air base)","formula":"B = (1 − overlap)·(photo width · ground scale)"},{"name":"Parallax height","formula":"h = H − f·B/p"},{"name":"Map scale conversion","formula":"ground = map distance × scale denominator"},{"name":"Grade (slope)","formula":"grade % = (ΔElev / horizontal distance) × 100"},{"name":"Average end-area volume","formula":"V = L·(A₁ + A₂)/2"},{"name":"Prismoidal volume","formula":"V = L·(A₁ + 4·A_m + A₂)/6"}]'::jsonb, '[{"type":"overview","title":"Module Overview","content":"## Mapping the world, then building on it\n\n**Mapping Processes and Methods** (14–21 of 110 questions) is the FS knowledge area that turns measurements into maps, and **photogrammetry, remote sensing, and GIS** are its high-yield computational and conceptual core. This module also reaches into **Surveying Processes** (construction layout, as-builts, quantities) and **Survey Computations** (earthwork volumes, slopes and grades), because the same student who can scale an aerial photo is expected to stake a building pad and compute the dirt to move.\n\n**Photogrammetry** is the science of making measurements from photographs. From a single vertical aerial photo you can recover **scale** (`S = f/(H−h)`), correct for **relief displacement** (tall objects lean away from the photo center), and from a **stereo pair** you can measure heights via **parallax**. Modern practice replaces film with digital sensors, so the key map-resolution metric is now the **ground sample distance (GSD)** — the ground size of one pixel.\n\n**Remote sensing** broadens this to non-photographic sensors: multispectral and hyperspectral satellite imagery, **LiDAR** (active laser ranging that yields dense 3-D point clouds and bare-earth DEMs), and **UAS/drone** platforms that have transformed small-area mapping.\n\n**GIS** stores and analyzes spatial data in two models — **vector** (points/lines/polygons with attributes) and **raster** (a grid of cells) — and depends on correctly declared **projections, coordinate systems, and datums** (NAD83 horizontal, NAVD88 vertical) plus **metadata**. Mis-declared projections are the classic GIS blunder.\n\nFinally, **construction surveying** lays the design back onto the ground: setting line and grade, computing **cut/fill** and **slope stakes**, and quantifying **earthwork** by the average-end-area and prismoidal formulas. Every formula here matches the **NCEES FS Reference Handbook v2.5** (Photogrammetry, Curvature & refraction, Earthwork sections) so the on-screen exam reference will look familiar."},{"type":"concepts","title":"Key Concepts","content":"## Photogrammetry — vertical photo geometry\n\nA **vertical aerial photograph** is taken with the camera axis (nearly) pointing straight down. The geometry is a perspective projection through the lens of **focal length f** at a **flying height H** above a datum; a point of ground height **h** sits at flying height **(H − h)** above it.\n\n- **Scale** of a vertical photo at a point of elevation h: `S = f / (H − h)`. Scale is a ratio (e.g., 1:6,000); it is **larger** (closer to 1) for low ground and high points, **smaller** for valleys. Use an **average scale** with `h = h_avg` for the whole photo.\n- **Scale as a distance ratio:** `S = (photo distance) / (ground distance)`. So `ground distance = photo distance / S` and `photo distance = ground distance × S`. Keep f, H, and h in **consistent units** (convert f in mm to feet, or H to mm) before dividing.\n- **Relief displacement** `d = r·h / H`: features above the datum are displaced **radially outward** from the principal point (photo center) by an amount proportional to the radial distance **r** and the object height **h**, and inversely to flying height **H**. This is why a building leans outward in an aerial photo — and the basis for measuring object heights from a single photo (`h = d·H/r`).\n\n## Digital sensors and GSD\n\nDigital cameras record a grid of pixels; the ground footprint of one pixel is the **ground sample distance**:\n\n`GSD = (pixel size × H) / f`\n\nwith pixel size, H, and f in **consistent units**. A handy shortcut: **GSD(cm) = pixel(µm) × H(m) / [f(mm) × 10]**. Smaller GSD = higher resolution. Flight planning trades GSD against flying height and flight time.\n\n## Stereo, overlap, and parallax\n\nAerial blocks are flown with ~**60% forward overlap** (endlap) and ~**30% sidelap** so every point appears on at least two photos, forming a **stereo model**. The horizontal distance between successive exposure stations is the **air base B**. **Parallax** `p = x − x′` is the difference in a point''s photo position between the two images; greater parallax = closer to the camera = higher ground. Heights come from `h = H − f·B/p`, or differentially from `h₂ = h₁ + [(p₂ − p₁)/p₂]·(H − h₁)`.\n\n## Remote sensing and LiDAR\n\n- **Passive remote sensing** records reflected/emitted energy across spectral bands (visible, near-IR, thermal). **Multispectral/hyperspectral** imagery supports land-cover classification and vegetation indices (e.g., NDVI).\n- **LiDAR** is **active** — it emits laser pulses and times the returns to build a dense 3-D **point cloud**. Multiple returns let it penetrate vegetation; classified ground returns produce a **bare-earth DEM**. Accuracy depends on GNSS/IMU positioning of the platform.\n- **UAS/drones** carry cameras or small LiDAR for low-altitude, high-resolution mapping of small sites; products include orthomosaics, DSMs, and point clouds via **structure-from-motion (SfM)**.\n\n## Maps, terrain models, and GIS data\n\n- **Map scale** is the ratio of map distance to ground distance (1:1,200 means 1 unit on the map = 1,200 on the ground). **Contours** connect points of equal elevation; the **contour interval** is the vertical spacing.\n- **Terrain models:** a **TIN** (triangulated irregular network) and **DEM/DSM** represent the surface; a **DSM** includes objects (canopy, buildings), a **DEM/DTM** is bare earth.\n- **GIS data models:** **vector** stores discrete features (points, lines, polygons) with **attributes**; **raster** stores a continuous grid of cells (each holding a value). Vector is efficient for discrete boundaries; raster suits continuous phenomena (elevation, imagery).\n- **Projections, coordinate systems, datums:** every spatial layer must declare its **projection** (Lambert Conformal Conic for E–W-extended states; Transverse Mercator for N–S states), **coordinate system** (e.g., SPCS), and **datum** (NAD83 horizontal, NAVD88 vertical; geoid undulation N relates ellipsoidal h to orthometric H via h = H + N). **Metadata** documents source, accuracy, and lineage. The #1 GIS failure is layers in mismatched/undeclared projections that don''t overlay.\n\n## Construction surveying\n\n- **Stakeout (layout)** places stakes that mark horizontal position (line/offset) and vertical position (grade/cut-fill) for construction. Offset stakes sit a known distance from the feature so they survive excavation.\n- **Grade** = the slope of a surface, usually expressed as a **percent**: `grade% = (ΔElev / horizontal distance) × 100`. A +2.0% grade rises 2 ft per 100 ft.\n- **Cut and fill:** at a station, **cut** = existing − proposed (remove material); **fill** = proposed − existing (add material). **Slope stakes** mark where the design side slope (e.g., 2:1, run:rise) meets existing ground.\n- **As-built (record) surveys** verify the finished work against design.\n\n## Earthwork volumes\n\nFrom cross-section **end areas** A₁, A₂ a distance L apart:\n\n- **Average end area:** `V = L·(A₁ + A₂)/2` — simple, slightly overestimates for transitioning sections.\n- **Prismoidal:** `V = L·(A₁ + 4·A_m + A₂)/6`, with A_m the area of the **mid-section** (not the average of A₁,A₂) — more accurate. Convert ft³ to **cubic yards** by ÷27. Apply **shrinkage** (fill compacts) or **swell** (excavated material bulks) factors as specified."},{"type":"formulas","title":"Essential Formulas","content":"## Photogrammetry (vertical photos)\n\n| Quantity | Formula | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Photo scale | `S = f / (H − h)` | f, H, h in consistent units; S is a ratio |\n| Scale as distance ratio | `S = photo dist / ground dist` | |\n| Ground distance | `D = d_photo / S = d_photo·(H − h)/f` | |\n| Photo distance | `d_photo = D·S` | |\n| Average scale | `S_avg = f / (H − h_avg)` | use mean ground elevation |\n| Flying height above ground | `H − h = f / S` | invert the scale relation |\n| Relief displacement | `d = r·h / H` | radial, outward from principal point |\n| Object height from displacement | `h = d·H / r` | |\n\n**Unit tip:** with f in millimeters and H, h in feet, convert f to feet first (`f_ft = f_mm/304.8`) or convert H to mm — never mix.\n\n## Ground sample distance (digital sensors)\n\n`GSD = (pixel size × H) / f`   (consistent units)\n\nShortcut: `GSD(cm) = pixel(µm) × H(m) / [f(mm) × 10]`\n\n## Stereo / parallax\n\n| Quantity | Formula |\n|---|---|\n| Parallax | `p = x − x′` |\n| Ground X, Y (parallax) | `X = x·B/p`,  `Y = y·B/p` |\n| Height from parallax | `h = H − f·B/p` |\n| Differential height | `h₂ = h₁ + [(p₂ − p₁)/p₂]·(H − h₁)` |\n| Air base (ground units) | `B = (1 − endlap)·(ground width of photo)` |\n\n(B = air base = ground distance between exposure stations; endlap ≈ 0.60, sidelap ≈ 0.30.)\n\n## Map scale conversions\n\n| Need | Relation |\n|---|---|\n| Ground from map | `ground = map dist × scale denominator` |\n| Map from ground | `map dist = ground / scale denominator` |\n| Engineer''s scale 1 in = N ft | scale denominator = N × 12 |\n\n## Grades and slopes\n\n`grade % = (ΔElev / horizontal distance) × 100`     `ΔElev = grade × horizontal distance`\n\nSide slope **s:1** (run:rise) means horizontal run = s × vertical rise.\n\n## Earthwork volumes\n\n| Method | Formula |\n|---|---|\n| Average end area | `V = L·(A₁ + A₂)/2` |\n| Prismoidal | `V = L·(A₁ + 4·A_m + A₂)/6` |\n| Pyramid/cone | `V = h·(base area)/3` |\n| ft³ → yd³ | `÷ 27` |\n\n## Height systems (mapping/GIS)\n\n`h = H + N` — ellipsoidal height h, orthometric height H (NAVD88), geoid undulation N. Declare horizontal datum (NAD83) and vertical datum (NAVD88) in metadata."},{"type":"examples","title":"Worked Examples","content":"## Vertical-photo geometry\n\nThe figure shows a vertical aerial photo: camera at flying height **H** above datum, focal length **f**, a ground point **A** at elevation **h**, and its image **a** at radial distance **r** from the principal point. Relief displacement leans **A** outward.\n\n<svg width=\"480\" height=\"320\" viewBox=\"0 0 480 320\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" style=\"background:#fff;border:1px solid #ccc\">\n  <!-- ground / datum -->\n  <line x1=\"30\" y1=\"280\" x2=\"450\" y2=\"280\" stroke=\"#7a5a2a\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n  <text x=\"360\" y=\"298\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#7a5a2a\">datum (h = 0)</text>\n  <!-- terrain bump for point A -->\n  <line x1=\"300\" y1=\"280\" x2=\"300\" y2=\"230\" stroke=\"#2a7a2a\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n  <text x=\"306\" y=\"258\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#2a7a2a\">h</text>\n  <circle cx=\"300\" cy=\"230\" r=\"4\" fill=\"#c0392b\"/>\n  <text x=\"306\" y=\"228\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"bold\">A</text>\n  <!-- camera / focal plane -->\n  <line x1=\"120\" y1=\"70\" x2=\"320\" y2=\"70\" stroke=\"#1c4e80\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n  <text x=\"322\" y=\"66\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#1c4e80\">focal plane (photo)</text>\n  <circle cx=\"190\" cy=\"40\" r=\"5\" fill=\"#333\"/>\n  <text x=\"198\" y=\"38\" font-size=\"12\">L (lens)</text>\n  <!-- focal length f -->\n  <line x1=\"190\" y1=\"40\" x2=\"190\" y2=\"70\" stroke=\"#888\" stroke-dasharray=\"3,3\"/>\n  <text x=\"196\" y=\"58\" font-size=\"12\">f</text>\n  <!-- principal point and image a -->\n  <circle cx=\"190\" cy=\"70\" r=\"3\" fill=\"#1c4e80\"/>\n  <text x=\"168\" y=\"86\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#1c4e80\">pp</text>\n  <circle cx=\"250\" cy=\"70\" r=\"4\" fill=\"#c0392b\"/>\n  <text x=\"252\" y=\"64\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#c0392b\">a</text>\n  <line x1=\"190\" y1=\"70\" x2=\"250\" y2=\"70\" stroke=\"#c0392b\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n  <text x=\"206\" y=\"84\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#c0392b\">r</text>\n  <!-- ray lens to A through a -->\n  <line x1=\"190\" y1=\"40\" x2=\"300\" y2=\"230\" stroke=\"#999\" stroke-dasharray=\"2,2\"/>\n  <!-- flying height H -->\n  <line x1=\"60\" y1=\"40\" x2=\"60\" y2=\"280\" stroke=\"#555\"/>\n  <text x=\"40\" y=\"160\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#555\">H</text>\n  <line x1=\"55\" y1=\"40\" x2=\"65\" y2=\"40\" stroke=\"#555\"/>\n  <line x1=\"55\" y1=\"280\" x2=\"65\" y2=\"280\" stroke=\"#555\"/>\n</svg>\n\n---\n\n## Example 1 — Photo scale of a vertical photograph\n\nA vertical photo is taken with a **f = 152.4 mm** (6.00 in) camera from a flying height **H = 6,000 ft** above datum. The ground beneath averages **h = 1,000 ft**. Find the average scale.\n\n1. Put f in feet: `f = 152.4 mm ÷ 304.8 = 0.500 ft` (6.00 in = 0.500 ft).\n2. Flying height above the ground: `H − h = 6,000 − 1,000 = 5,000 ft`.\n3. `S = f/(H − h) = 0.500 / 5,000 = 1/10,000`.\n\n**Scale = 1:10,000** (1 in on the photo = 10,000 in = 833.3 ft on the ground).\n\n**Calculator (TI-36X Pro):** `0.5 ÷ 5000 =` → `1×10⁻⁴`; take the reciprocal `x⁻¹` → **10,000**, so 1:10,000. **Casio fx-991:** identical. Watch the **unit conversion** of f from mm to ft — the single most common photogrammetry error.\n\n---\n\n## Example 2 — Ground distance from a photo measurement\n\nOn the photo of Example 1 (scale 1:10,000), two road intersections are **3.20 in** apart. What is their ground distance?\n\n1. `ground = photo distance / S = 3.20 in × 10,000 = 32,000 in`.\n2. `32,000 ÷ 12 = 2,666.7 ft`.\n\n**Ground distance ≈ 2,666.7 ft.** Equivalently `D = d·(H − h)/f = 3.20 × 5,000 / 0.5 in`-consistent — keep units straight. **Calculator:** `3.2 × 10000 ÷ 12 =`.\n\n---\n\n## Example 3 — Ground sample distance (digital sensor)\n\nA UAS camera has a **5.2 µm** pixel and **f = 24 mm** focal length, flown at **H = 400 m** above ground. Find the GSD.\n\n1. Shortcut form: `GSD(cm) = pixel(µm) × H(m) / [f(mm) × 10] = 5.2 × 400 / (24 × 10)`.\n2. `= 2,080 / 240 = 8.67 cm`.\n\n**GSD ≈ 8.7 cm/pixel.** Check the full form: `GSD = (5.2×10⁻⁶ m × 400 m)/(0.024 m) = 0.0867 m = 8.67 cm`. ✓\n\n**Calculator (Casio fx-991):** `5.2 × 400 ÷ ( 24 × 10 ) =` → 8.667. Confirm with the SI form using `×10^x` for the µm→m and mm→m conversions.\n\n---\n\n## Example 4 — Relief displacement\n\nA radio tower images at radial distance **r = 4.50 in** from the principal point. Its top is **h = 500 ft** above the datum; flying height **H = 5,000 ft**. Find the relief displacement and the tower height if measured displacement is 0.45 in.\n\n1. **Predicted displacement:** `d = r·h/H = 4.50 × 500 / 5,000 = 0.45 in` (the top leans 0.45 in outward from its base).\n2. **Inverting to get height** from a measured `d = 0.45 in`: `h = d·H/r = 0.45 × 5,000 / 4.50 = 500 ft`. ✓\n\n**Calculator:** `4.5 × 500 ÷ 5000 =` → 0.45. Relief displacement is **radial**, so always measure r and d from the **principal point**, not the photo corner.\n\n---\n\n## Example 5 — Flying height from a required scale\n\nA mapping job specifies photos at **1:12,000** with a **f = 6.00 in (0.500 ft)** camera over flat ground at elevation **h = 0**. What flying height above the ground is required?\n\n1. `H − h = f / S = 0.500 / (1/12,000) = 0.500 × 12,000 = 6,000 ft`.\n2. With h = 0, the flying height above datum **H = 6,000 ft**.\n\n**Flying height = 6,000 ft above ground.** **Calculator:** `0.5 × 12000 =`.\n\n---\n\n## Example 6 — Earthwork volume by average end area\n\nTwo adjacent cross-sections **100 ft apart** have end areas **A₁ = 220 ft²** and **A₂ = 380 ft²**. Find the cut volume in cubic yards.\n\n1. `V = L·(A₁ + A₂)/2 = 100 × (220 + 380)/2 = 100 × 300 = 30,000 ft³`.\n2. `÷ 27 = 1,111 yd³`.\n\n**V ≈ 1,111 yd³.** If a mid-section area A_m = 305 ft² were given, the **prismoidal** result would be `V = 100·(220 + 4·305 + 380)/6 = 100·(1,820)/6 = 30,333 ft³ = 1,123 yd³`. **Calculator:** `100 × ( 220 + 380 ) ÷ 2 ÷ 27 =`."},{"type":"tips","title":"Exam Tips & Calculator Strategy","content":"## Strategy for the mapping area\n\n- **Photogrammetry items are mostly one-formula plug-ins** (`S = f/(H−h)`, `GSD`, `d = r·h/H`, map-scale ratios). They are fast points if you keep **units consistent** — convert f from mm to ft (÷304.8) or H from ft to mm before dividing. Budget ~2 min each and bank them.\n- **GIS/remote-sensing/mapping concept questions are even faster** — vector vs. raster, datum/projection, LiDAR vs. passive, contour interval. These are recall points; answer them on sight and save calculator time for COGO.\n- **Construction/earthwork items** reuse Module-5 skills: grade %, cut/fill, and the average-end-area/prismoidal volume formulas. Remember **÷27 for cubic yards** and the **A_m is the mid-section area, not the average**.\n\n## Approved-calculator tricks (TI-36X Pro / Casio fx-991 / HP-35S)\n\n- **Scale is a ratio:** compute `f/(H−h)` then press **x⁻¹** (reciprocal) to read the scale denominator (e.g., 1×10⁻⁴ → 10,000 → 1:10,000).\n- **Unit conversions:** TI-36X Pro and Casio have a **convert/constants** menu, but it''s faster to memorize `1 ft = 304.8 mm`, `1 m = 3.2808 ft`, `1 in = 25.4 mm`. Use **×10^x** for µm (×10⁻⁶) and mm (×10⁻³) in the GSD SI form.\n- **GSD shortcut** avoids unit juggling entirely: `GSD(cm) = pixel(µm)·H(m)/[f(mm)·10]` — one keystroke chain.\n- **Store the flying height** (STO) when several photo-scale parts share the same H to avoid re-keying.\n- **Earthwork:** chain `L×(A₁+A₂)÷2÷27` in one expression; use the calculator''s fraction/parenthesis entry to avoid order-of-operations slips.\n\n## Common traps\n\n- **Mixing units in the scale formula** — f in mm but H in ft. Convert first. This is the #1 photogrammetry mistake.\n- **Scale direction:** scale gets **larger** (denominator smaller) for **higher** ground (smaller H−h). Hilltops are at larger scale than valleys on the same photo.\n- **Relief displacement is radial** — r and d are measured from the **principal point**, and the displacement is **outward** for points above the datum.\n- **Average end area vs. prismoidal:** A_m is the **mid-section** area, NOT (A₁+A₂)/2. Average-end-area slightly **overestimates**; the prismoidal correction reduces it.\n- **Cubic yards:** divide ft³ by **27**, not 9. And watch shrinkage (compacted fill needs *more* bank volume) vs. swell.\n- **Datum vs. projection vs. coordinate system** are three different things in GIS — a layer needs all three declared to overlay correctly; geoid undulation N links ellipsoidal and orthometric heights (h = H + N).\n- **DSM vs. DEM/DTM:** DSM includes objects (canopy, buildings); DEM/DTM is bare earth — LiDAR last-return/ground-classified points give the DEM.\n\n## How the handbook helps\n\nThe NCEES FS Reference Handbook v2.5 lists the **Photogrammetry** block (scale `f/(H−h)`, relief displacement `r·h/H`, parallax forms, flying height) and the **Earthwork** block (average end area, prismoidal, pyramid) verbatim, plus **Conversions** (ft↔m, in↔mm, acre, the 43,560 and 27 factors). Know *where* the Photogrammetry and Earthwork sections sit in the Mathematical & Surveying-Related Formulas chapter so you can confirm a formula in seconds rather than deriving it under time pressure."}]'::jsonb, 7, 70, 34, '🛩️', 450, true, 'approved')
ON CONFLICT (module_number) DO UPDATE SET title=EXCLUDED.title, description=EXCLUDED.description, week_range=EXCLUDED.week_range, exam_weight_percent=EXCLUDED.exam_weight_percent, key_topics=EXCLUDED.key_topics, key_formulas=EXCLUDED.key_formulas, content_sections=EXCLUDED.content_sections, prerequisite_module=EXCLUDED.prerequisite_module, question_count=EXCLUDED.question_count, icon=EXCLUDED.icon, xp_reward=EXCLUDED.xp_reward, is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now();
  'fb085000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', 'Vertical photo scale', 'Vertical photo scale', 'FS — Mapping & Photogrammetry', 'Photogrammetry', 'numeric_input', 'easy', 'A vertical aerial photo is taken with a focal length of {{f_ft:f3}} ft from a flying height of {{H:f0}} ft above datum, over ground at an average elevation of {{h:f0}} ft. Compute the photo SCALE denominator (report N for a scale of 1:N).', 'round((H-h)/f_ft,0)', '{"decimals":0,"unit":"","tolerance":5}', '[{"name":"f_ft","type":"float","min":0.3,"max":0.7,"decimals":3},{"name":"H","type":"float","min":4000,"max":12000,"decimals":0},{"name":"h","type":"float","min":0,"max":1500,"decimals":0}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Flying height above ground","formula":"H − h","calculation_template":"{{H:f0}} − {{h:f0}} = {{_d:f0}} ft"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Scale = f/(H − h); denominator = (H − h)/f","result_template":"1:{{_answer}}"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Photo scale S = f/(H−h). With f = {{f_ft:f3}} ft and H−h = {{H:f0}} − {{h:f0}} ft, the scale denominator N = (H−h)/f = {{_answer}}, i.e. a scale of 1:{{_answer}}. Keep f, H, and h in the same units.', 'f5000008-0000-0000-0000-000000000008', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m8','fs-practice']::text[], NULL, true, 'fs:m8');
  'fb085000-0000-0000-0000-000000000002', 'Ground distance from a photo measurement', 'Ground distance from a photo measurement', 'FS — Mapping & Photogrammetry', 'Photogrammetry', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'On a vertical photo at scale 1:{{scale:f0}}, two features are measured {{dphoto:f2}} in apart. Compute the corresponding GROUND distance, in feet.', 'dphoto*scale/12', '{"decimals":1,"unit":"ft","tolerance":1}', '[{"name":"scale","type":"float","min":3000,"max":20000,"decimals":0},{"name":"dphoto","type":"float","min":1.5,"max":6,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Ground = photo distance × scale denominator","calculation_template":"{{dphoto:f2}} in × {{scale:f0}} = {{_inch:f0}} in"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Convert inches to feet (÷12)","result_template":"{{_answer}} ft"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Ground distance = photo distance × scale denominator = {{dphoto:f2}} in × {{scale:f0}} = ground inches; divide by 12 for feet → {{_answer}} ft. Scale is the ratio photo/ground, so ground = photo ÷ S.', 'f5000008-0000-0000-0000-000000000008', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m8','fs-practice']::text[], NULL, true, 'fs:m8');
  'fb085000-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', 'Ground sample distance (GSD)', 'Ground sample distance (GSD)', 'FS — Mapping & Photogrammetry', 'Photogrammetry', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'A digital aerial camera has a {{pix:f1}} µm pixel and a focal length of {{f_mm:f1}} mm, flown {{H:f0}} m above the ground. Compute the ground sample distance (GSD), in centimeters.', 'pix*H/(f_mm*10)', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"cm","tolerance":0.05}', '[{"name":"pix","type":"float","min":3,"max":8,"decimals":1},{"name":"f_mm","type":"float","min":16,"max":50,"decimals":1},{"name":"H","type":"float","min":120,"max":1500,"decimals":0}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"GSD shortcut (cm)","formula":"GSD = pixel(µm)·H(m)/[f(mm)·10]","calculation_template":"{{pix:f1}} × {{H:f0}} / ({{f_mm:f1}} × 10)"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Result","result_template":"GSD = {{_answer}} cm/pixel"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Using the unit-matched shortcut GSD(cm) = pixel(µm)·H(m)/[f(mm)·10] = {{pix:f1}}·{{H:f0}}/({{f_mm:f1}}·10) = {{_answer}} cm. Smaller GSD means higher resolution.', 'f5000008-0000-0000-0000-000000000008', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m8','fs-practice']::text[], NULL, true, 'fs:m8');
  'fb085000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'Relief displacement', 'Relief displacement', 'FS — Mapping & Photogrammetry', 'Photogrammetry', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'On a vertical photo, an object images at a radial distance r = {{r:f2}} in from the principal point. The object top is {{h:f0}} ft above the datum and the flying height is H = {{H:f0}} ft. Compute the relief displacement d, in inches.', 'r*h/H', '{"decimals":3,"unit":"in","tolerance":0.005}', '[{"name":"r","type":"float","min":1.5,"max":5,"decimals":2},{"name":"h","type":"float","min":100,"max":800,"decimals":0},{"name":"H","type":"float","min":3000,"max":9000,"decimals":0}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Relief displacement","formula":"d = r·h/H","calculation_template":"{{r:f2}} × {{h:f0}} / {{H:f0}}"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Result","result_template":"d = {{_answer}} in (radially outward)"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Relief displacement d = r·h/H = {{r:f2}} × {{h:f0}} / {{H:f0}} = {{_answer}} in. The displacement is radial and outward from the principal point for points above the datum.', 'f5000008-0000-0000-0000-000000000008', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m8','fs-practice']::text[], NULL, true, 'fs:m8');
  'fb085000-0000-0000-0000-000000000005', 'Flying height from required scale', 'Flying height from required scale', 'FS — Mapping & Photogrammetry', 'Photogrammetry', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'A mapping flight requires a photo scale of 1:{{scale:f0}} using a camera of focal length {{f_ft:f3}} ft over flat ground at the datum (h = 0). Compute the required FLYING HEIGHT above the ground, in feet.', 'f_ft*scale', '{"decimals":0,"unit":"ft","tolerance":2}', '[{"name":"scale","type":"float","min":3000,"max":20000,"decimals":0},{"name":"f_ft","type":"float","min":0.3,"max":0.7,"decimals":3}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Invert the scale relation","formula":"H − h = f/S = f × scale denominator","calculation_template":"{{f_ft:f3}} × {{scale:f0}}"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Result (h = 0)","result_template":"H = {{_answer}} ft above ground"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'From S = f/(H−h), the flying height above ground is H−h = f × scale denominator = {{f_ft:f3}} × {{scale:f0}} = {{_answer}} ft. With h = 0 at the datum, H = {{_answer}} ft.', 'f5000008-0000-0000-0000-000000000008', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m8','fs-practice']::text[], NULL, true, 'fs:m8');
  'fb085000-0000-0000-0000-000000000006', 'Map distance from ground distance', 'Map distance from ground distance', 'FS — Mapping & Photogrammetry', 'Mapping', 'numeric_input', 'easy', 'A ground line is {{dground:f1}} ft long. On a map at scale 1:{{scale:f0}}, how long will the line plot, in inches?', 'dground*12/scale', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"in","tolerance":0.02}', '[{"name":"dground","type":"float","min":400,"max":5000,"decimals":1},{"name":"scale","type":"float","min":600,"max":4800,"decimals":0}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Convert ground feet to inches","calculation_template":"{{dground:f1}} ft × 12 = {{_gin:f0}} in"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Map distance = ground / scale denominator","result_template":"{{_answer}} in"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Map distance = ground distance / scale denominator. Convert ground to inches: {{dground:f1}} ft × 12 = ground inches; ÷ {{scale:f0}} = {{_answer}} in on the map.', 'f5000008-0000-0000-0000-000000000008', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m8','fs-practice']::text[], NULL, true, 'fs:m8');
  'fb085000-0000-0000-0000-000000000007', 'Earthwork volume by average end area', 'Earthwork volume by average end area', 'FS — Plane Survey Computations', 'Earthwork', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'Two cross-sections {{L:f0}} ft apart have end areas of {{A1:f0}} ft² and {{A2:f0}} ft². Using the average-end-area method, compute the volume between them, in cubic yards.', 'L*(A1+A2)/2/27', '{"decimals":1,"unit":"yd³","tolerance":1}', '[{"name":"L","type":"float","min":50,"max":200,"decimals":0},{"name":"A1","type":"float","min":80,"max":400,"decimals":0},{"name":"A2","type":"float","min":80,"max":400,"decimals":0}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"vcf","formula":"L*(A1+A2)/2"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Average end area volume (ft³)","formula":"V = L·(A₁+A₂)/2","calculation_template":"{{L:f0}} × ({{A1:f0}} + {{A2:f0}})/2 = {{vcf:f0}} ft³"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Convert to cubic yards (÷27)","result_template":"{{_answer}} yd³"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'V = L·(A₁+A₂)/2 = {{L:f0}} × ({{A1:f0}}+{{A2:f0}})/2 = {{vcf:f0}} ft³. Divide by 27 to convert to cubic yards: {{_answer}} yd³.', 'f5000008-0000-0000-0000-000000000008', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m8','fs-practice']::text[], NULL, true, 'fs:m8');
  'fb085000-0000-0000-0000-000000000008', 'Grade and elevation change', 'Grade and elevation change', 'FS — Plane Survey Computations', 'Construction', 'numeric_input', 'easy', 'A roadway is designed at a grade of {{grade:f2}}%. Over a horizontal distance of {{dist:f0}} ft, compute the change in elevation, in feet.', 'grade/100*dist', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"ft","tolerance":0.05}', '[{"name":"grade","type":"float","min":0.5,"max":6,"decimals":2},{"name":"dist","type":"float","min":100,"max":1200,"decimals":0}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"ΔElev = grade × horizontal distance","calculation_template":"({{grade:f2}}/100) × {{dist:f0}}"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Result","result_template":"ΔElev = {{_answer}} ft"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Grade as a decimal = {{grade:f2}}/100. ΔElev = grade × horizontal distance = ({{grade:f2}}/100) × {{dist:f0}} = {{_answer}} ft of rise (or fall, for a negative grade).', 'f5000008-0000-0000-0000-000000000008', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m8','fs-practice']::text[], NULL, true, 'fs:m8');

-- ===== FS Module 9: Approved Calculator Mastery & Test Strategy =====
DELETE FROM question_bank WHERE module_id='f5000009-0000-0000-0000-000000000009' AND 'fs-buildout' = ANY(tags);
DELETE FROM question_bank WHERE exam_category='FS-MOCK' AND 'fs-m9' = ANY(tags);
DELETE FROM problem_templates WHERE created_by='fs:m9';
VALUES ('f5000009-0000-0000-0000-000000000009', 9, 'Approved Calculator Mastery & Test Strategy', 'Turn your NCEES-approved calculator into a COGO machine: enter and add angles in DMS, convert DMS↔decimal, and use rectangular↔polar (R▸P / P▸R) to solve inverse and forward coordinate geometry in a single keystroke chain — then layer on the pacing, guessing, and handbook-search strategy that wins the timed FS exam.', 'Ongoing', 0, ARRAY['The 2026 NCEES approved-calculator list (Casio fx-115/991, HP 33s/35s, TI-30X/36X)','DMS entry, DMS arithmetic, and DMS↔decimal-degree conversion','Rectangular↔polar (R▸P / P▸R) as the one-step inverse and forward COGO engine','Inverse: distance and azimuth between two coordinates via R▸P','Forward: coordinates of a new point from azimuth + distance via P▸R','Bearing↔azimuth quadrant rules and back-azimuth','Memory registers (STO/RCL/SUM) to chain a traverse without re-keying','Area by coordinates (shoelace / sum of cross-products) on the calculator','Horizontal-curve quickies (T, L) under time pressure','FS time management, flag-and-return, guessing, and efficient handbook search']::text[], '[{"name":"DMS to decimal degrees","formula":"dec = D + M/60 + S/3600"},{"name":"DMS to total seconds","formula":"sec = D·3600 + M·60 + S"},{"name":"Inverse distance (R▸P r)","formula":"D = hypot(ΔN, ΔE) = √(ΔN² + ΔE²)"},{"name":"Inverse azimuth (R▸P θ)","formula":"Az = (toDeg(atan2(ΔE, ΔN)) + 360) mod 360"},{"name":"Forward latitude (P▸R)","formula":"ΔN = D·cos(Az)"},{"name":"Forward departure (P▸R)","formula":"ΔE = D·sin(Az)"},{"name":"Forward coordinates","formula":"N₂ = N₁ + D·cos(Az);  E₂ = E₁ + D·sin(Az)"},{"name":"Bearing→azimuth (by quadrant)","formula":"NE: Az = β;  SE: Az = 180 − β;  SW: Az = 180 + β;  NW: Az = 360 − β"},{"name":"Back azimuth","formula":"Az_back = (Az + 180) mod 360"},{"name":"Area by coordinates (shoelace)","formula":"A = ½·|Σ (Xᵢ·Y_{i+1} − X_{i+1}·Yᵢ)|"},{"name":"Tangent (curve quickie)","formula":"T = R·tan(I/2)"},{"name":"Curve length (curve quickie)","formula":"L = R·I·(π/180)"}]'::jsonb, '[{"type":"overview","title":"Module Overview","content":"## Speed is a skill — and it is the cheapest points on the FS\n\nThe FS gives you **110 questions in 5 hours 20 minutes — about 2.9 minutes each**. The boundary-law, ethics, and definition items are fast if you know them, but the computational questions (Survey Computations and Applied Math, ~27–41 of the 110) are where time *bleeds*. A surveyor who fumbles a DMS entry, hunts for the polar-conversion key, or hand-cranks an inverse with atan and quadrant bookkeeping will run out of clock before running out of knowledge. A surveyor whose calculator is an extension of their hand banks those points and buys time for the harder items. **Calculator fluency is the single highest-leverage exam skill that costs nothing but practice.**\n\nThis module is not new theory — Modules 4 and 5 already taught the COGO, traverse, area, and curve formulas. Here you learn to **execute** them at speed on an **NCEES-approved calculator**, and to spend the time you save wisely with deliberate test strategy.\n\n## The 2026 approved-calculator list\n\nNCEES limits you to a fixed list, **re-issued every year** (same list for FS, FE, PS, PE). **No programmable, graphing, or CAS calculators.** For **2026**:\n\n- **Casio** — all **fx-115** and **fx-991** models (the name must contain \"fx-115\" or \"fx-991\").\n- **Hewlett Packard** — **HP 33s** and **HP 35s** only (no other HP).\n- **Texas Instruments** — all **TI-30X** and **TI-36X** models (the name must contain \"TI-30X\" or \"TI-36X\").\n\n**Buy and master one of two:** the **TI-36X Pro** (the most-recommended FS/FE calculator — DMS, polar↔rectangular, matrices, stats, solver, two-line MathPrint display) or the **Casio fx-991EX ClassWiz** (fast, large display, excellent DMS/stat, TABLE mode). The HP 33s/35s are **discontinued** and use RPN — great for COGO chaining if you already love RPN, but not worth learning from scratch. **Always confirm the current year''s list on ncees.org before your exam**, and bring a **second approved calculator** as a backup."},{"type":"concepts","title":"Key Concepts","content":"## The five operations every surveyor must own\n\nMaster these and you can solve almost every FS computational item quickly:\n\n1. **DMS entry & arithmetic** — type, add, and subtract angles in degrees-minutes-seconds.\n2. **DMS ↔ decimal degrees** — convert in one keystroke, both directions.\n3. **Rectangular → polar (R▸P)** — turns (ΔE, ΔN) into (distance, angle): the **inverse** in one step.\n4. **Polar → rectangular (P▸R)** — turns (distance, azimuth) into (ΔE, ΔN): the **forward** in one step.\n5. **Memory registers** — STO/RCL (and SUM where available) to chain a traverse without re-keying coordinates.\n\n## DMS entry, arithmetic, and conversion\n\nSurvey angles are **degrees-minutes-seconds** (e.g., 257°44′10″). Both approved families convert and compute in DMS natively, so you never have to hand-convert.\n\n- **TI-36X Pro:** the angle key is **[2nd][DMS]** (the `°′″` menu). Enter `257°44′10″` as `257 [2nd][DMS]°  44 [2nd][DMS]′  10 [2nd][DMS]″`. To **convert a decimal to DMS**, compute the value then `[2nd][DMS] → ▸DMS`. To go **DMS → decimal**, just enter the DMS value and the calculator already stores it as decimal internally.\n- **Casio fx-991EX:** the key is **[°′″]**. Enter `257 [°′″] 44 [°′″] 10 [°′″]`. Pressing **[°′″]** again (or `SHIFT [°′″]` → `▸DMS`) toggles the **answer** between decimal degrees and D°M′S″.\n- **HP-33S/35S:** store angles as **H.MMSSss** and convert with **→HR** (HMS→decimal) and **→HMS** (decimal→HMS).\n- **Arithmetic in DMS:** you can add/subtract angles directly — e.g., balancing interior angles, or summing a deflection. Enter each angle in DMS and press `+`/`−`; the result displays in DMS (or convert as needed). Keep the calculator in **DEGREE (DEG) mode** so all trig uses degrees.\n\n## Why R▸P / P▸R is the heart of COGO\n\nA survey leg has two equivalent descriptions: **rectangular** (ΔE, ΔN) = (departure, latitude), and **polar** (distance, direction). The calculator''s built-in conversions move between them **in one step**, replacing a whole chain of `√`, `atan`, and quadrant logic:\n\n- **Inverse** (two coordinates → distance + azimuth): compute `ΔE = E₂ − E₁` and `ΔN = N₂ − N₁`, feed them to **R▸P**, and read **distance** and **azimuth** directly. The calculator''s R▸P returns the angle measured from the x-axis with the correct sign — combine with the handbook quadrant constant (or use `atan2`) to land in 0–360° azimuth.\n- **Forward** (point + azimuth + distance → new coordinates): feed **distance** and **azimuth** to **P▸R** and read **ΔE (departure)** and **ΔN (latitude)** directly, then add to the start point. This *is* `ΔN = D·cos(Az)`, `ΔE = D·sin(Az)` done in one operation.\n\n**Convention used here (matches the RPLS notes):** treat **x = ΔE (Easting/departure)** and **y = ΔN (Northing/latitude)**, with the angle measured as an **azimuth from north**. Some calculators define the polar angle from the x-axis; if yours does, enter ΔN as x and ΔE as y (or swap the read-out) so the angle comes out as an azimuth. Drill *your own* unit until you know which slot is which without thinking.\n\n## Angle modes — keep it in DEG\n\nSet the calculator to **DEGREE (DEG)** mode and confirm the **DEG** indicator before any trig. A calculator left in **RAD** or **GRAD** is the classic silent blunder — answers will be wildly wrong with no error message. Curve, traverse, and inverse work all assume degrees.\n\n## Memory registers — chain a traverse\n\nUse **STO/RCL** (TI: `[sto→]`/`[rcl]`; Casio: `[STO]`/`[RCL]` with variables A,B,C,…,X,Y,M) to hold running Northing and Easting totals so you never re-key a coordinate. On the TI-30Xa the **[SUM+]** key accumulates a value into memory — the basis of the leg-by-leg traverse routine in Part B. Store a constant like the vertical-curve parabola term or a fixed radius once, then reuse it. **Every value you re-key is a chance for a blunder; store it instead.**\n\n## Fractions, reciprocals, and other time-savers\n\n- **Reciprocal `x⁻¹`** reads a scale denominator (e.g., `f/(H−h)` then `x⁻¹`) or converts relative precision to a 1:N ratio.\n- **Fraction entry** (TI MathPrint, Casio Natural display) lets you type `(A₁+A₂)/2` as a stacked fraction, avoiding order-of-operations slips.\n- **Ans** recalls the last result to chain calculations; **parentheses** protect order of operations in long expressions.\n- **Stat mode** (mean, sample σ) handles repeated-measurement and error-propagation items without summing by hand."},{"type":"formulas","title":"Essential Formulas","content":"## Each survey task → the calculator operation that solves it\n\n| Survey task | Math | Calculator operation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Convert a field angle to decimal | `dec = D + M/60 + S/3600` | enter in **DMS**, read decimal (toggle) |\n| Convert a decimal answer to DMS | — | **▸DMS** (TI `[2nd][DMS]`, Casio `SHIFT[°′″]`) |\n| Add/subtract angles | balance / deflection sums | enter each in **DMS**, `+` / `−` |\n| **Inverse** (two pts → distance) | `D = hypot(ΔN, ΔE)` | **R▸P**, read r |\n| **Inverse** (two pts → azimuth) | `Az = (toDeg(atan2(ΔE,ΔN)) + 360) mod 360` | **R▸P**, read θ, then quadrant constant |\n| **Forward** (az+dist → coords) | `ΔN = D·cos(Az)`, `ΔE = D·sin(Az)` | **P▸R**, read ΔE and ΔN |\n| Bearing → azimuth | quadrant rule (below) | mental + DMS |\n| Azimuth → bearing | quadrant rule (below) | mental + DMS |\n| Back azimuth | `Az_back = (Az + 180) mod 360` | `±180` |\n| Area from coordinates | `A = ½·|Σ(Xᵢ·Y_{i+1} − X_{i+1}·Yᵢ)|` | sum of cross-products, ÷2, abs |\n| Curve tangent | `T = R·tan(I/2)` | DEG mode, `tan(I/2)` |\n| Curve length | `L = R·I·(π/180)` | `R × I × π ÷ 180` or `(I/D)·100` |\n\n## Bearing ↔ azimuth quadrant rules (memorize)\n\nAzimuth runs **0–360° clockwise from north**. A bearing is a **quadrant letter + acute angle β**:\n\n| Quadrant | Bearing → Azimuth | Azimuth → Bearing |\n|---|---|---|\n| **NE** (Az 0–90) | `Az = β` | `N β E` |\n| **SE** (Az 90–180) | `Az = 180 − β` | `S (180−Az) E` |\n| **SW** (Az 180–270) | `Az = 180 + β` | `S (Az−180) W` |\n| **NW** (Az 270–360) | `Az = 360 − β` | `N (360−Az) W` |\n\nThe **sign of ΔN and ΔE** fixes the quadrant on an inverse: ΔN+/ΔE+ → NE; ΔN−/ΔE+ → SE; ΔN−/ΔE− → SW; ΔN+/ΔE− → NW.\n\n## Inverse — the azimuth, robustly\n\nThe one-line bare-helper form that always lands in 0–360°:\n\n`Az = (toDeg(atan2(ΔE, ΔN)) + 360) − 360·floor((toDeg(atan2(ΔE, ΔN)) + 360)/360)`\n\nNote the argument order **atan2(ΔE, ΔN)** — easting first, northing second — because azimuth is measured from north (the ΔN axis). On the calculator, R▸P does this for you; the formula is the fallback when you key it by hand.\n\n## DMS as total seconds (handy for drills/precision)\n\n`total seconds = D·3600 + M·60 + S`, and back: `D = floor(sec/3600)`, `M = floor((sec mod 3600)/60)`, `S = sec mod 60`.\n\n## Combined-factor and other one-key chains\n\n- **Grid from ground:** `grid = ground × combined factor`; **ground from grid:** `ground = grid / combined factor`. Store the combined factor, multiply/divide.\n- **Scale denominator:** compute the ratio, press `x⁻¹`.\n- **Relative precision:** `misclosure ÷ perimeter`, then `x⁻¹` for 1:N."},{"type":"examples","title":"Worked Examples","content":"## Keystroke notation\n\n`[2nd]`, `[SHIFT]`, `[°′″]`, `[R▸P]`, `[P▸R]`, `[x⇄y]`, `[▸DMS]` are calculator keys. **Always confirm DEGREE (DEG) mode first.** Where the TI and Casio differ, both are shown; HP-33S/35S (RPN) is noted where the Part-B resources give it.\n\n<svg width=\"460\" height=\"300\" viewBox=\"0 0 460 300\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" style=\"background:#fff;border:1px solid #ccc\">\n  <!-- axes: x = E (departure), y = N (latitude) -->\n  <line x1=\"60\" y1=\"250\" x2=\"420\" y2=\"250\" stroke=\"#333\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n  <line x1=\"110\" y1=\"280\" x2=\"110\" y2=\"30\" stroke=\"#333\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n  <text x=\"425\" y=\"254\" font-size=\"12\">+E (departure, x)</text>\n  <text x=\"86\" y=\"26\" font-size=\"12\">+N (latitude, y)</text>\n  <!-- leg from P1 to P2 -->\n  <circle cx=\"110\" cy=\"250\" r=\"4\" fill=\"#1c4e80\"/>\n  <text x=\"82\" y=\"266\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#1c4e80\">P1</text>\n  <circle cx=\"330\" cy=\"110\" r=\"4\" fill=\"#c0392b\"/>\n  <text x=\"338\" y=\"108\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#c0392b\">P2</text>\n  <line x1=\"110\" y1=\"250\" x2=\"330\" y2=\"110\" stroke=\"#c0392b\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n  <text x=\"205\" y=\"170\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#c0392b\">D (r)</text>\n  <!-- delta E and delta N legs -->\n  <line x1=\"110\" y1=\"250\" x2=\"330\" y2=\"250\" stroke=\"#1a5\" stroke-dasharray=\"4,3\"/>\n  <text x=\"200\" y=\"266\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#1a5\">ΔE</text>\n  <line x1=\"330\" y1=\"250\" x2=\"330\" y2=\"110\" stroke=\"#1a5\" stroke-dasharray=\"4,3\"/>\n  <text x=\"336\" y=\"185\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#1a5\">ΔN</text>\n  <!-- azimuth arc from north -->\n  <path d=\"M 110 200 A 50 50 0 0 1 145 165\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#7a5a2a\" stroke-width=\"1.3\"/>\n  <text x=\"120\" y=\"180\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#7a5a2a\">Az</text>\n  <text x=\"150\" y=\"292\" font-size=\"11\" fill=\"#555\">R▸P: (ΔE, ΔN) → (D, Az)   ·   P▸R: (D, Az) → (ΔE, ΔN)</text>\n</svg>\n\n---\n\n## Example 1 — Enter and ADD two angles in DMS\n\nAdd interior angles **48°17′35″** and **63°42′50″** (e.g., checking an angle sum).\n\n**TI-36X Pro:** `48 [2nd][DMS]° 17 [2nd][DMS]′ 35 [2nd][DMS]″  +  63 [2nd][DMS]° 42 [2nd][DMS]′ 50 [2nd][DMS]″  =` → `112.0069°`; press `[2nd][DMS] ▸DMS` → **112°00′25″**.\n\n**Casio fx-991EX:** `48 [°′″] 17 [°′″] 35 [°′″] + 63 [°′″] 42 [°′″] 50 [°′″] =` → toggles to **112°00′25″** (press `[°′″]` to switch the answer form).\n\n**Check:** 35″ + 50″ = 85″ = 1′25″; 17′ + 42′ + 1′ = 60′ = 1°; 48° + 63° + 1° = **112°00′25″**. ✓ Subtraction works identically with `−` (used for angle balancing).\n\n---\n\n## Example 2 — Convert DMS ↔ decimal degrees\n\nConvert **257°44′10″** to decimal, then convert **330.5°** to DMS.\n\n1. **DMS → decimal.** `dec = 257 + 44/60 + 10/3600 = 257 + 0.733333 + 0.002778 = 257.7361°`.\n   - **TI-36X Pro:** enter `257 [2nd][DMS]° 44 ′ 10 ″  =` → reads **257.7361°** (already decimal internally).\n   - **Casio fx-991EX:** `257 [°′″] 44 [°′″] 10 [°′″] =`, then `[°′″]` to show **257.7361°**.\n2. **decimal → DMS.** `330.5°`: 0.5° × 60 = 30′ → **330°30′00″**.\n   - **TI:** `330.5 [2nd][DMS] ▸DMS` → **330°30′00″**. **Casio:** `330.5 = SHIFT[°′″](▸DMS)` → **330°30′00″**. **HP-35S:** `330.5 →HMS` → 330.3000 (read as 330°30′00″).\n\n---\n\n## Example 3 — INVERSE between two coordinates via R▸P (distance + azimuth)\n\nP1 (N 17,095.842, E 44,600.312) and P2 (N 16,917.920, E 43,781.054). Find the distance and azimuth P1→P2.\n\n1. **Differences:** `ΔE = E₂ − E₁ = 43,781.054 − 44,600.312 = −819.258`; `ΔN = N₂ − N₁ = 16,917.920 − 17,095.842 = −177.922`. Both negative → **SW quadrant**.\n2. **Distance:** `D = hypot(ΔN, ΔE) = √(177.922² + 819.258²) = √(31,656 + 671,184) = √702,840 = 838.36 ft`.\n3. **R▸P keystrokes (TI-36X Pro):** `[2nd][R▸P]` with `(ΔE, ΔN)`: enter `−819.258 [,] −177.922 [)] =`; the `r` field reads **838.36** (distance) and the `θ` field reads the angle. Press `[x⇄y]` to read θ.\n   - **Casio fx-991EX:** `[SHIFT][+](Pol)`  `Pol(−819.258 , −177.922) =` → returns `r = 838.36`, `θ`. (Casio Pol takes (x, y); here x = ΔE, y = ΔN.)\n   - **TI-30Xa (Part-B method):** enter `ΔE [2nd][x⇄y] ΔN [2nd][R▸P]` → DIST; `[2nd][x⇄y]` → angle; `[2nd][▸DMS]` for DMS.\n4. **Azimuth:** the bare-helper form `Az = (toDeg(atan2(ΔE, ΔN)) + 360) mod 360 = (toDeg(atan2(−819.258, −177.922)) + 360) mod 360`. atan2(−819.258, −177.922) → −102.256° → +360 = 257.744° → **Az = 257°44′37″** (SW: 180° + bearing 77°44′37″). ✓ matches the Part-B worked sample (~257°44′).\n\n**One inverse = one R▸P.** No separate √, no separate atan, no quadrant table if you trust atan2.\n\n---\n\n## Example 4 — Coordinates of a point from azimuth + distance via P▸R\n\nFrom P1 (N 5,000.00, E 5,000.00), go **azimuth 330°30′00″**, **distance 200.00 ft**. Find the new point.\n\n1. **Latitude/Departure:** `ΔN = D·cos(Az) = 200·cos(330.5°) = 200·0.87036 = +174.07`; `ΔE = D·sin(Az) = 200·sin(330.5°) = 200·(−0.49242) = −98.48` (NW: ΔN+, ΔE−). ✓ matches Part-B sample.\n2. **P▸R keystrokes (TI-36X Pro):** `[2nd][P▸R]`  `P▸R(200 , 330.5) =` → returns the two rectangular components; one is ΔE = **−98.48**, press `[x⇄y]` for ΔN = **+174.07**.\n   - **Casio fx-991EX:** `[SHIFT][−](Rec)`  `Rec(200 , 330.5) =` → `x = +174.07, y = −98.48` (Casio Rec returns (x along the polar axis); map x→ΔN, y→ΔE under the north-azimuth convention — confirm on your unit).\n   - **TI-30Xa (Part-B method):** `200 [2nd][x⇄y] 330.5 [2nd][P▸R]` → DEP (ΔE); `[2nd][x⇄y]` → LAT (ΔN).\n3. **New coordinates:** `N₂ = 5,000.00 + 174.07 = 5,174.07`; `E₂ = 5,000.00 − 98.48 = 4,901.52`.\n\n**P2 ≈ (N 5,174.07, E 4,901.52).** One P▸R replaces two trig calls.\n\n---\n\n## Example 5 — Bearing ↔ azimuth\n\n(a) Convert bearing **S 36°15′ W** to azimuth. SW quadrant → `Az = 180° + β = 180° + 36°15′ =` **216°15′00″**.\n\n(b) Convert azimuth **295°40′** to a bearing. NW quadrant (270–360) → `bearing = N (360° − Az) W = N (360° − 295°40′) W = N 64°20′ W`.\n\n**Keystrokes:** do the `180 +`, `360 −` in **DMS**: e.g., TI `180 [2nd][DMS]° + 36 ° 15 ′ =` → **216°15′00″**; Casio `360 [°′″] − 295 [°′″] 40 [°′″] =` → **64°20′00″**. **Back azimuth** is just `Az ± 180`: 216°15′ → 36°15′; 64°20′ → 244°20′.\n\n---\n\n## Example 6 — AREA by coordinates (sum of cross-products)\n\nFour corners in order — A(N 1,000, E 1,000), B(N 1,000, E 1,400), C(N 1,300, E 1,400), D(N 1,300, E 1,000) — using **X = E, Y = N**.\n\n1. **Cross-products** `Σ(Xᵢ·Y_{i+1} − X_{i+1}·Yᵢ)`:\n   - A→B: 1000·1000 − 1400·1000 = −400,000\n   - B→C: 1400·1300 − 1400·1000 = +420,000\n   - C→D: 1400·1300 − 1000·1300 = +520,000\n   - D→A: 1000·1000 − 1000·1300 = −300,000\n   - Σ = +240,000\n2. **Area:** `A = ½·|240,000| = 120,000 ft²` → ÷ 43,560 = **2.755 acres** (a 400 × 300 rectangle ✓).\n\n**Keystrokes:** chain it on one line with parentheses, or store each `Xᵢ·Y_{i+1} − X_{i+1}·Yᵢ` with `[SUM+]`/`+` into memory, then `[RCL] ÷ 2 [x⇄y]`. On the **HP-33S/35S** the stored **AREA** routine accepts sequential N,E and returns acreage directly. **Tip:** for a quick rectangle, don''t run a full routine — just multiply the sides.\n\n---\n\n## Example 7 — Horizontal-curve quickie (T and L)\n\nR = 1,145.92 ft, deflection I = 24°00′00″. Find T and L fast.\n\n1. **Tangent:** `T = R·tan(I/2) = 1145.92·tan(12°) = 1145.92·0.212557 = 243.57 ft`.\n2. **Length:** `L = R·I·(π/180) = 1145.92·(24·π/180) = 1145.92·0.418879 = 480.00 ft` (or `(I/D)·100` with D = 5729.58/R = 5.000° → (24/5)·100 = 480.00 ✓).\n\n**Keystrokes (TI-36X Pro, DEG):** `1145.92 × tan( 24 ÷ 2 ) =` → 243.57; `1145.92 × 24 × π ÷ 180 =` → 480.00. **Casio fx-991EX:** identical. **Time-saver:** when D is given, `(I/D)·100` skips π entirely. Type `I/2` directly into `tan(` — don''t compute I/2 separately."},{"type":"tips","title":"Exam Tips & Calculator Strategy","content":"## NCEES calculator rules (don''t get turned away at the door)\n\n- Your calculator **must be on the current approved list** (2026: Casio fx-115/fx-991, HP 33s/35s, TI-30X/36X). **No programmable, graphing, or CAS** models. The proctor checks it.\n- **Clear all memory** before the exam if your model can store programs/notes — NCEES expects a cleared calculator. Stored COGO programs from the HP program books are **not** allowed on the actual exam (they were study/field references, not test tools).\n- Bring a **second approved calculator** and **fresh batteries** (or solar + light). A dead calculator mid-exam is catastrophic and avoidable.\n- **Confirm the list on ncees.org for your exam year** — it is re-issued annually and a model can drop off.\n\n## Calculator discipline that prevents blunders\n\n- **DEG mode, always** — verify the DEG indicator before any trig. RAD/GRAD is the silent killer.\n- **Store, don''t re-key.** Use STO/RCL for running N/E totals and reused constants; every re-typed number is a blunder risk.\n- **One inverse, one R▸P; one forward, one P▸R.** Don''t hand-crank √ + atan + quadrant — let the conversion do it, and trust atan2 for the quadrant.\n- **Sanity-check the quadrant** from the signs of ΔN, ΔE (NE/SE/SW/NW). If a point can''t be SW of a known point, an azimuth near 200° is wrong.\n- **Round only at the end.** Carry full precision; format with ▸DMS or fixed decimals last.\n- **Use the simplest method.** Don''t run a traverse routine to area a rectangle (Part D guidance) — multiply the sides.\n\n## Time management & test strategy (from the Part-D strategies)\n\n- **Pace ≈ 2.9 min/question** (110 in 5 h 20 min). Keep momentum, not raw speed.\n- **7-step flow:** (1) preview the exam, (2) answer the **easiest first**, (3) **flag and skip** hard ones, (4) calculate, (5) **eliminate** wrong answers, (6) **educated guess**, (7) use leftover time to **review**.\n- **Bank the fast points first:** boundary-law, ethics, and definition items are quick if known — don''t let a 6-minute COGO problem early in the exam starve them of time.\n- **Read the whole problem before keying anything** — don''t enter every given coordinate until you know which corners/lines the question actually needs (Part-D calculation discipline). Solve each inverse/value **once** and store it.\n- **Make a margin sketch** (vicinity sketch) for COGO/traverse/curve items — it prevents quadrant and PC/PT stationing errors.\n\n## Guessing & flag-and-return\n\n- **There is no penalty for wrong answers** — **never leave a question blank.** Answer every one before time expires.\n- **Eliminate with strike-throughs**, then guess among what''s left; watch for **distracters** that are too broad/narrow or off by a unit (ft vs. m, 27 vs. 9, 5729.58 vs. 5730).\n- **Clues hide in other questions'' preambles** — a definition or value you need may appear elsewhere.\n- **Flag-and-return:** mark long multi-step items, move on, and come back with the time you banked from the quick ones. **Trust your gut** on split decisions; change an answer only with a concrete reason.\n\n## Using the electronic FS Reference Handbook efficiently\n\n- The handbook (**v2.5**) and the standards PDFs are searchable and open the **entire exam** — but the handbook is **big**. **Know where each formula lives** (DMS/trig, Inverse & quadrant constant, Horizontal/Vertical curves, Area formulas, Earthwork, Photogrammetry, Probability & statistics) so you **confirm**, not hunt.\n- **Practice with the actual PDF from MyNCEES** before exam day; learn the search terms that jump to each section.\n- The handbook gives the **inverse quadrant constant C** (0/180/180/360) and the curve formulas verbatim — pair them with your R▸P/P▸R muscle memory so the calculator does the arithmetic and the handbook only confirms the form.\n\n## Common traps\n\n- Calculator in **RAD** instead of DEG. · Mixing **ΔE/ΔN order** into atan2 (azimuth uses atan2(ΔE, ΔN)). · Reading **r** when you wanted **θ** (or vice versa) after R▸P — press `[x⇄y]`. · Forgetting the **quadrant constant** so a SW azimuth reads as NE. · `PT = PC + L` (arc), **not** PC + 2T. · **÷27** for cubic yards, **÷43,560** for acres — don''t swap. · Leaving an item **blank** (always guess)."}]'::jsonb, 8, 70, 32, '🧮', 500, true, 'approved')
ON CONFLICT (module_number) DO UPDATE SET title=EXCLUDED.title, description=EXCLUDED.description, week_range=EXCLUDED.week_range, exam_weight_percent=EXCLUDED.exam_weight_percent, key_topics=EXCLUDED.key_topics, key_formulas=EXCLUDED.key_formulas, content_sections=EXCLUDED.content_sections, prerequisite_module=EXCLUDED.prerequisite_module, question_count=EXCLUDED.question_count, icon=EXCLUDED.icon, xp_reward=EXCLUDED.xp_reward, is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now();
  'fb095000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', 'DMS to total seconds (calculator drill)', 'DMS to total seconds (calculator drill)', 'FS — Calculator Skills', 'DMS', 'numeric_input', 'easy', 'CALCULATOR CHALLENGE — Express the angle {{D:f0}}°{{M:f0}}′{{S:f0}}″ as a TOTAL number of seconds.', 'D*3600 + M*60 + S', '{"decimals":0,"unit":"sec","tolerance":0.5}', '[{"name":"D","type":"integer","min":0,"max":359},{"name":"M","type":"integer","min":0,"max":59},{"name":"S","type":"integer","min":0,"max":59}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Seconds = D·3600 + M·60 + S","calculation_template":"{{D:f0}}·3600 + {{M:f0}}·60 + {{S:f0}}"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Result","result_template":"{{_answer}} seconds"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Total seconds = D·3600 + M·60 + S = {{D:f0}}·3600 + {{M:f0}}·60 + {{S:f0}} = {{_answer}} seconds. A fast mental/keystroke drill that underlies DMS arithmetic.', 'f5000009-0000-0000-0000-000000000009', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m9','fs-practice']::text[], NULL, true, 'fs:m9');
  'fb095000-0000-0000-0000-000000000002', 'DMS + DMS angle sum (calculator drill)', 'DMS + DMS angle sum (calculator drill)', 'FS — Calculator Skills', 'DMS', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'CALCULATOR CHALLENGE — Add the two angles {{D1:f0}}°{{M1:f0}}′{{S1:f0}}″ and {{D2:f0}}°{{M2:f0}}′{{S2:f0}}″ and report the SUM in DECIMAL degrees.', '(D1 + M1/60 + S1/3600) + (D2 + M2/60 + S2/3600)', '{"decimals":4,"unit":"°","tolerance":0.001}', '[{"name":"D1","type":"integer","min":5,"max":120},{"name":"M1","type":"integer","min":0,"max":59},{"name":"S1","type":"integer","min":0,"max":59},{"name":"D2","type":"integer","min":5,"max":120},{"name":"M2","type":"integer","min":0,"max":59},{"name":"S2","type":"integer","min":0,"max":59}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Convert each to decimal","formula":"dec = D + M/60 + S/3600","calculation_template":"{{D1:f0}}+{{M1:f0}}/60+{{S1:f0}}/3600 and {{D2:f0}}+{{M2:f0}}/60+{{S2:f0}}/3600"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Add","result_template":"{{_answer}}°"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Enter both angles in DMS, press +, and the calculator returns the sum; here in decimal it is ({{D1:f0}}+{{M1:f0}}/60+{{S1:f0}}/3600) + ({{D2:f0}}+{{M2:f0}}/60+{{S2:f0}}/3600) = {{_answer}}°. Toggle ▸DMS for the field-book form.', 'f5000009-0000-0000-0000-000000000009', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m9','fs-practice']::text[], NULL, true, 'fs:m9');
  'fb095000-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', 'Inverse distance via R▸P (calculator drill)', 'Inverse distance via R▸P (calculator drill)', 'FS — Calculator Skills', 'COGO', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'CALCULATOR CHALLENGE (R▸P) — Point A is at (N {{nA:f2}}, E {{eA:f2}}) and point B is at (N {{nB:f2}}, E {{eB:f2}}). Using rectangular-to-polar, compute the horizontal DISTANCE A→B (ft).', 'hypot(dN,dE)', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"ft","tolerance":0.1}', '[{"name":"nA","type":"float","min":1000,"max":5000,"decimals":2},{"name":"eA","type":"float","min":1000,"max":5000,"decimals":2},{"name":"dN","type":"float","min":-1500,"max":1500,"decimals":2},{"name":"dE","type":"float","min":-1500,"max":1500,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"nB","formula":"nA+dN"},{"name":"eB","formula":"eA+dE"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Latitude & departure","calculation_template":"ΔN = {{nB:f2}} − {{nA:f2}} = {{dN:f2}}; ΔE = {{eB:f2}} − {{eA:f2}} = {{dE:f2}}"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Distance = √(ΔN²+ΔE²) via R▸P","result_template":"{{_answer}} ft (read r)"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Compute ΔN = {{dN:f2}} and ΔE = {{dE:f2}}, feed them to R▸P, and read the distance r = hypot(ΔN, ΔE) = {{_answer}} ft. One R▸P replaces the separate √ and atan.', 'f5000009-0000-0000-0000-000000000009', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m9','fs-practice']::text[], '{"type":"inverse","aNVar":"nA","aEVar":"eA","bNVar":"nB","bEVar":"eB","aLabel":"A","bLabel":"B","title":"Inverse via R▸P (distance)"}'::jsonb, true, 'fs:m9');
  'fb095000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'Inverse azimuth via R▸P (calculator drill)', 'Inverse azimuth via R▸P (calculator drill)', 'FS — Calculator Skills', 'COGO', 'numeric_input', 'hard', 'CALCULATOR CHALLENGE (R▸P) — Point A is at (N {{nA:f2}}, E {{eA:f2}}) and point B is at (N {{nB:f2}}, E {{eB:f2}}). Using rectangular-to-polar, compute the AZIMUTH A→B in decimal degrees (0–360°).', '(toDeg(atan2(dE,dN))+360) - 360*floor((toDeg(atan2(dE,dN))+360)/360)', '{"decimals":4,"unit":"°","tolerance":0.01}', '[{"name":"nA","type":"float","min":1000,"max":5000,"decimals":2},{"name":"eA","type":"float","min":1000,"max":5000,"decimals":2},{"name":"dN","type":"float","min":-1500,"max":1500,"decimals":2},{"name":"dE","type":"float","min":-1500,"max":1500,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"nB","formula":"nA+dN"},{"name":"eB","formula":"eA+dE"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Latitude & departure","calculation_template":"ΔN = {{dN:f2}}, ΔE = {{dE:f2}} (signs fix the quadrant)"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Azimuth via atan2 / R▸P θ","formula":"Az = (toDeg(atan2(ΔE, ΔN)) + 360) mod 360","result_template":"{{_answer}}°"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Azimuth is measured from north: Az = atan2(ΔE, ΔN) normalized to 0–360°. With ΔE = {{dE:f2}}, ΔN = {{dN:f2}}, Az = {{_answer}}°. On the calculator, R▸P returns this θ directly — read it with the swap key.', 'f5000009-0000-0000-0000-000000000009', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m9','fs-practice']::text[], '{"type":"inverse","aNVar":"nA","aEVar":"eA","bNVar":"nB","bEVar":"eB","aLabel":"A","bLabel":"B","title":"Inverse via R▸P (azimuth)"}'::jsonb, true, 'fs:m9');
  'fb095000-0000-0000-0000-000000000005', 'Forward coordinate via P▸R (calculator drill)', 'Forward coordinate via P▸R (calculator drill)', 'FS — Calculator Skills', 'COGO', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'CALCULATOR CHALLENGE (P▸R) — From point P (N {{nP:f2}}, E {{eP:f2}}) go azimuth {{az:f2}}° a distance of {{dist:f2}} ft. Using polar-to-rectangular, compute the NORTHING of the new point (ft).', 'nP + dist*cos(toRad(az))', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"ft","tolerance":0.1}', '[{"name":"nP","type":"float","min":1000,"max":5000,"decimals":2},{"name":"eP","type":"float","min":1000,"max":5000,"decimals":2},{"name":"az","type":"float","min":0,"max":359.99,"decimals":2},{"name":"dist","type":"float","min":50,"max":1500,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"dN","formula":"dist*cos(toRad(az))"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Latitude from P▸R","formula":"ΔN = D·cos(Az)","calculation_template":"{{dist:f2}}·cos({{az:f2}}°) = {{dN:f2}}"},{"step_number":2,"title":"New Northing","result_template":"N = {{nP:f2}} + {{dN:f2}} = {{_answer}} ft"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Feed distance {{dist:f2}} and azimuth {{az:f2}}° to P▸R; the latitude ΔN = D·cos(Az) = {{dN:f2}} ft. New Northing = {{nP:f2}} + {{dN:f2}} = {{_answer}} ft.', 'f5000009-0000-0000-0000-000000000009', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m9','fs-practice']::text[], '{"type":"traverse","startNVar":"nP","startEVar":"eP","legs":[{"azVar":"az","distVar":"dist","label":"P→Q"}],"title":"Forward via P▸R"}'::jsonb, true, 'fs:m9');
  'fb095000-0000-0000-0000-000000000006', 'Bearing to azimuth (SW quadrant drill)', 'Bearing to azimuth (SW quadrant drill)', 'FS — Calculator Skills', 'Directions', 'numeric_input', 'easy', 'CALCULATOR CHALLENGE — A line has the bearing S {{beta:f2}}° W. Compute its AZIMUTH (decimal degrees, 0–360°).', '180 + beta', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"°","tolerance":0.01}', '[{"name":"beta","type":"float","min":1,"max":89,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"SW quadrant rule","formula":"Az = 180° + β","calculation_template":"180 + {{beta:f2}}"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Result","result_template":"Az = {{_answer}}°"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'A southwest bearing converts by Az = 180° + β = 180 + {{beta:f2}} = {{_answer}}°. (NE: β; SE: 180−β; SW: 180+β; NW: 360−β.)', 'f5000009-0000-0000-0000-000000000009', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m9','fs-practice']::text[], NULL, true, 'fs:m9');
  'fb095000-0000-0000-0000-000000000007', 'Area by coordinates (triangle, shoelace drill)', 'Area by coordinates (triangle, shoelace drill)', 'FS — Calculator Skills', 'Area', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'CALCULATOR CHALLENGE — A triangular parcel has corners, in order, A (N {{nA:f2}}, E {{eA:f2}}), B (N {{nB:f2}}, E {{eB:f2}}), and C (N {{nC:f2}}, E {{eC:f2}}). Using the coordinate (shoelace) method, compute the area in SQUARE FEET.', 'abs((eA*nB-eB*nA)+(eB*nC-eC*nB)+(eC*nA-eA*nC))/2', '{"decimals":1,"unit":"ft²","tolerance":1}', '[{"name":"nA","type":"float","min":1000,"max":1200,"decimals":2},{"name":"eA","type":"float","min":1000,"max":1200,"decimals":2},{"name":"nB","type":"float","min":1000,"max":1500,"decimals":2},{"name":"eB","type":"float","min":1300,"max":1700,"decimals":2},{"name":"nC","type":"float","min":1300,"max":1700,"decimals":2},{"name":"eC","type":"float","min":1000,"max":1300,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Use X = Easting, Y = Northing","calculation_template":"A({{eA:f2}},{{nA:f2}}), B({{eB:f2}},{{nB:f2}}), C({{eC:f2}},{{nC:f2}})"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Sum of cross-products, halved, absolute value","formula":"A = ½|Σ(Xᵢ·Y_{i+1} − X_{i+1}·Yᵢ)|","result_template":"{{_answer}} ft²"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Apply the shoelace sum with X = Easting, Y = Northing around A→B→C, halve the absolute value: A = ½|Σ(Xᵢ·Y_{i+1} − X_{i+1}·Yᵢ)| = {{_answer}} ft². Chain the three cross-products with memory/SUM to avoid re-keying.', 'f5000009-0000-0000-0000-000000000009', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m9','fs-practice']::text[], '{"type":"triangle","vertices":[{"nVar":"nA","eVar":"eA","label":"A"},{"nVar":"nB","eVar":"eB","label":"B"},{"nVar":"nC","eVar":"eC","label":"C"}],"title":"Area by coordinates"}'::jsonb, true, 'fs:m9');
  'fb095000-0000-0000-0000-000000000008', 'Horizontal-curve quickie — tangent T (calculator drill)', 'Horizontal-curve quickie — tangent T (calculator drill)', 'FS — Calculator Skills', 'Curves', 'numeric_input', 'easy', 'CALCULATOR CHALLENGE — A circular curve has R = {{R:f2}} ft and deflection angle I = {{I:f2}}°. In DEGREE mode, compute the tangent distance T (ft).', 'R*tan(toRad(I/2))', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"ft","tolerance":0.1}', '[{"name":"R","type":"float","min":400,"max":2000,"decimals":2},{"name":"I","type":"float","min":8,"max":75,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Tangent = R·tan(I/2)","formula":"T = R·tan(I/2)","calculation_template":"{{R:f2}}·tan({{I:f2}}/2°)"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Result","result_template":"T = {{_answer}} ft"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'In DEGREE mode, type I/2 straight into tan: T = R·tan(I/2) = {{R:f2}}·tan({{I:f2}}°/2) = {{_answer}} ft.', 'f5000009-0000-0000-0000-000000000009', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m9','fs-practice']::text[], '{"type":"curve","rVar":"R","iVar":"I","title":"Horizontal curve: tangent T"}'::jsonb, true, 'fs:m9');

-- ===== FS Module 10: Comprehensive Review & Final Mock Exam =====
DELETE FROM question_bank WHERE module_id='f500000a-0000-0000-0000-00000000000a' AND 'fs-buildout' = ANY(tags);
DELETE FROM question_bank WHERE exam_category='FS-MOCK' AND 'fs-m10' = ANY(tags);
DELETE FROM problem_templates WHERE created_by='fs:m10';
VALUES ('f500000a-0000-0000-0000-00000000000a', 10, 'Comprehensive Review & Final Mock Exam', 'The capstone: a high-yield condensed review across all seven FS knowledge areas, a one-page master formula sheet, mixed multi-step worked problems, and a two-week study plan — everything tied together to power the 110-question comprehensive final mock exam.', 'Final', 0, ARRAY['How the real NCEES FS exam works: 110 questions, 5 h 20 min CBT, closed-book with the electronic FS Reference Handbook at Pearson VUE','Condensed cram review of all seven knowledge areas (math/stats, processes, principles/geodesy, computations, mapping/photogrammetry, boundary law, business/ethics)','Dignity (priority) of calls and the hierarchy of boundary evidence','Master formula sheet pulling one key formula from every module','Mixed multi-step problems: traverse → misclosure → adjust → area','Error propagation, leveling, latitude/departure, inverse, area, curves, scale/GSD, H = h − N, grid/ground combined factor','Calculator fluency: DMS, R▸P / P▸R, statistics mode, store-and-recall','Two-week study plan, exam-day logistics, and time budget (~2.9 min/question)','Category proportions of the FS exam (boundary heaviest, then computations)','Final timed full-length mock exam under exam conditions']::text[], '[{"name":"Standard error of the mean","formula":"σ_m = σ / √n"},{"name":"Error propagation (sum)","formula":"σ_sum = √(σ₁² + σ₂² + … + σₙ²)"},{"name":"Differential leveling","formula":"HI = Elev + BS;  Elev = HI − FS"},{"name":"Latitude & departure","formula":"Lat = L·cos(Az);  Dep = L·sin(Az)"},{"name":"Linear misclosure & precision","formula":"misclose = √(ΣLat² + ΣDep²);  precision = misclose / perimeter"},{"name":"Inverse (distance)","formula":"D = √(ΔN² + ΔE²) = hypot(ΔN, ΔE)"},{"name":"Inverse (azimuth)","formula":"Az = atan2(ΔE, ΔN), reduced to 0–360°"},{"name":"Area by coordinates (shoelace)","formula":"A = ½·|Σ (Xᵢ·Y_{i+1} − X_{i+1}·Yᵢ)|"},{"name":"Horizontal curve tangent","formula":"T = R·tan(I/2)"},{"name":"Horizontal curve length","formula":"L = R·I·(π/180)"},{"name":"Vertical curve elevation","formula":"Y = Y_PVC + g₁·x + [(g₂−g₁)/(2L)]·x²"},{"name":"Photo scale","formula":"S = f / (H − h)"},{"name":"Ground sample distance","formula":"GSD = (pixel size · H) / f"},{"name":"Geoid relationship","formula":"H = h − N  (h = ellipsoidal, H = orthometric, N = geoid undulation)"},{"name":"Grid ↔ ground (combined factor)","formula":"grid = ground · CF;  ground = grid / CF;  CF = SF · EF"}]'::jsonb, '[{"type":"overview","title":"Module Overview","content":"## The capstone: review everything, then take the mock\n\nYou have worked through the math/stats, field, computation, geodesy, mapping, boundary, and business modules. This final module does two things: it **condenses the whole course into a high-yield cram review**, and it **powers the 110-question comprehensive final mock exam** that simulates the real test.\n\n## How the real FS exam works\n\n- **110 questions** delivered as a **computer-based test (CBT)** at a **Pearson VUE** center, offered year-round.\n- **6-hour appointment:** 2-min nondisclosure agreement · 8-min tutorial · **5 h 20 min of exam time** · a 25-min scheduled break. That leaves roughly **2.9 minutes per question**.\n- **Closed-book**, but you get the **electronic NCEES FS Reference Handbook** (current published version 2.x) on screen the entire exam, plus searchable PDF standards (ALTA/NSPS, FEMA, FGCS leveling, GPAS, NSPS Model Standards, USNMAS). **No personal references.**\n- **Pass/fail only** — no numeric score. Results in 7–10 business days via MyNCEES; a failing report breaks down performance by area.\n- The seven knowledge areas are **not** equally weighted. **Boundary Law & Real Property is the single largest area (19–29 questions)**, followed by **Survey Computations (17–26)** and **Surveying Processes (16–24)**. Treat the FS as a boundary-and-computation exam as much as a math exam.\n\n## How to use this review + mock\n\nWork the **Key Concepts** cram sheet to refresh every area, keep the **master formula sheet** beside you, and grind the **mixed worked examples** — the real exam chains topics (a curve buried inside an area problem, error propagation on a measured area). Then take the **final mock under timed, closed-book conditions** using only the handbook, and review every miss against its category. The mock is built so the category mix mirrors the real exam, so your diagnostic mirrors what NCEES would report."},{"type":"concepts","title":"Key Concepts","content":"## Cram sheet — the most-tested facts in every area\n\n### Applied math & statistics (Area 7)\n- **Standard error of the mean** σ_m = σ/√n; **sample std dev** σ = √[Σv²/(n−1)].\n- **Error propagation:** sum/inverse-type σ_sum = √(Σσᵢ²); a series of n equal measurements σ_series = σ·√n; product (area) σ = √[(B·σ_a)² + (A·σ_b)²].\n- **Weights ∝ 1/σ²**; weighted mean = Σ(W·x)/ΣW.\n- **Normal curve:** 68 / 95 / 99.7% at 1 / 2 / 3σ. 95% two-tail Z = 1.960.\n- **Blunder vs systematic vs random** — only random errors follow the normal curve; systematic errors are removed by correction, blunders by checks/redundancy.\n\n### Surveying processes & methods (Area 1)\n- **GNSS:** static (highest accuracy, long sessions), RTK/kinematic (real-time, baseline-limited), **OPUS** (post-process a single static occupation against CORS).\n- **Control hierarchy:** horizontal/vertical networks, network design, accuracy standards; occupy from the whole to the part.\n- **Field records:** raw data files and field books are the evidence of the work — keep them complete and unaltered.\n- **EDM atmospheric correction:** ~10 ppm per 10 °C or per 1 in Hg.\n\n### Surveying principles & geodesy (Area 4)\n- **Geoid** = equipotential surface ⟂ to gravity (mean sea level idealized); the **ellipsoid** is the smooth math reference. **H = h − N** (orthometric = ellipsoidal − geoid undulation).\n- **Datums:** NAD83 (horizontal), NAVD88 (vertical). **Lambert Conformal Conic** for E–W states, **Transverse Mercator** for N–S states (SPCS).\n- **Convergence** (mapping angle) relates geodetic north to grid north.\n- Spherical trig for long lines; **spherical excess** for large triangles.\n\n### Survey computations (Area 5)\n- **Leveling:** HI = Elev + BS; Elev = HI − FS; ΣBS − ΣFS = ΔElev. **(c & r) ≈ 0.0206·D²** ft (D in thousands of ft); reciprocal leveling cancels it.\n- **Inverse:** D = hypot(ΔN, ΔE); Az = atan2(ΔE, ΔN) reduced to 0–360°.\n- **Traverse:** Lat = L·cos Az, Dep = L·sin Az; misclosure = √(ΣLat²+ΣDep²); precision = misclosure/perimeter; **Bowditch** correction ∝ leg length/perimeter.\n- **Area by coordinates** (shoelace); **curves** T = R·tan(I/2), L = R·I·(π/180), **PT = PC + L** (add the arc!).\n- **Vertical curve:** Y = Y_PVC + g₁x + [(g₂−g₁)/(2L)]x²; turning point x = −g₁L/(g₂−g₁).\n- **Volume:** average end area V = L(A₁+A₂)/2; ÷27 for yd³.\n\n### Mapping, GIS & photogrammetry (Area 2)\n- **Photo scale** S = f/(H−h); **GSD** = pixel·H/f; **relief displacement** d = r·h/H.\n- **Vector vs raster**; map projections, datums, and **metadata** (the data about the data — required for sharing).\n- **Contours** never cross; closer spacing = steeper ground. **TIN / DEM / DSM** terrain models.\n- Map types: topographic, planimetric, plat, **ALTA/NSPS**, plan-and-profile.\n\n### Boundary law & real property (Area 3 — the heaviest)\n- **Dignity (priority) of conflicting calls — controlling order:**\n  1. **Senior rights** (the earlier conveyance wins in a sequential split).\n  2. **Written intentions of the parties** (the controlling intent in the deed).\n  3. **Calls for monuments** — natural (river, tree) over artificial (iron pin), and monuments over courses and distances.\n  4. **Calls for direction (bearing)** over distance.\n  5. **Calls for distance.**\n  6. **Calls for area (quantity)** — least reliable, controls last.\n- **Senior/junior rights:** in a **sequential** conveyance the first grantee takes the full called area; the **remainder (junior) parcel absorbs any excess or deficiency**. **Simultaneous** conveyances (a single recorded plat) **prorate** excess/deficiency among lots.\n- **PLSS:** township = 36 sections; Section 1 is NE corner, numbered boustrophedon; restore lost corners by **single/double proportionate measurement**; obliterated corners by collateral evidence.\n- **Adverse possession:** open, notorious, continuous, hostile, exclusive for the statutory period.\n- **Easement** = a non-possessory right to use another''s land; **appurtenant** runs with the land and passes with conveyance; created by grant, reservation, implication, necessity, or prescription.\n- **Water:** **accretion** (gradual deposit, boundary moves), **avulsion** (sudden, boundary fixed); riparian (rivers) vs littoral (lakes/sea).\n- A **warranty deed** guarantees title; a **quitclaim** conveys only whatever interest the grantor has.\n\n### Business concepts & ethics (Area 6)\n- **Ethics — NSPS canons / Model Rules:** the surveyor''s **first and foremost duty is to public safety and welfare**; practice only within your **area of competence**; sign/seal **only work under your responsible charge**; keep client matters confidential; no misleading advertising.\n- **Contracts** need offer, acceptance, consideration, capacity, lawful purpose; scope of work and specifications define the deliverable.\n- **Liability:** negligence and **errors & omissions (E&O)**; the standard of care is what a reasonable surveyor would do.\n- **Safety:** **Risk = Hazard × Probability**; SDS has 16 sections; JSA/JHA documents step-by-step hazards.\n- **Economics:** simple/compound interest, present worth, straight-line depreciation D = (C − S)/n."},{"type":"formulas","title":"Essential Formulas","content":"## Master formula sheet — one key formula from every module\n\nKeep this beside you for the mock. Every entry matches the NCEES FS Reference Handbook v2.x.\n\n### Math & statistics\n| Quantity | Formula |\n|---|---|\n| Standard error of mean | `σ_m = σ/√n` |\n| Sample std deviation | `σ = √[Σv²/(n−1)]` |\n| Error propagation (sum/inverse) | `σ_sum = √(σ₁² + σ₂² + … + σₙ²)` |\n| Series of n equal measurements | `σ_series = σ·√n` |\n| Area (product) propagation | `σ_A = √[(B·σ_a)² + (A·σ_b)²]` |\n| Weighted mean | `M = Σ(W·x)/ΣW`,  `W ∝ 1/σ²` |\n\n### Field measurement & leveling\n| Quantity | Formula |\n|---|---|\n| Height of instrument | `HI = Elev + BS` |\n| New elevation | `Elev = HI − FS` |\n| Curvature & refraction (rod) | `(c & r) ≈ 0.0206·D²` ft  (D in 1000s ft) |\n| Slope → horizontal | `H = S·cos(zenith) = S·cos(vert. angle)` |\n| Tape temperature correction | `ΔL = α·L·(T − T₀)` |\n\n### Traverse & COGO\n| Quantity | Formula |\n|---|---|\n| Latitude / departure | `Lat = L·cos(Az)`,  `Dep = L·sin(Az)` |\n| Inverse distance | `D = hypot(ΔN, ΔE)` |\n| Inverse azimuth | `Az = atan2(ΔE, ΔN)` → 0–360° |\n| Forward coordinates | `N₂ = N₁ + D·cos(Az)`,  `E₂ = E₁ + D·sin(Az)` |\n| Linear misclosure | `misclose = √(ΣLat² + ΣDep²)` |\n| Relative precision | `precision = misclose / perimeter` |\n| Bowditch correction (per leg) | `c_lat = −ΣLat·(legL/perim)` (likewise dep) |\n\n### Area & volume\n| Quantity | Formula |\n|---|---|\n| Area by coordinates (shoelace) | `A = ½·\\|Σ (Xᵢ·Y_{i+1} − X_{i+1}·Yᵢ)\\|` |\n| Acres | `acres = ft² / 43,560` |\n| Average end-area volume | `V = L·(A₁ + A₂)/2` |\n| Cubic yards | `yd³ = ft³ / 27` |\n\n### Curves\n| Quantity | Formula |\n|---|---|\n| Degree of curve (arc) | `D = 5,729.58 / R` |\n| Tangent | `T = R·tan(I/2)` |\n| Curve length | `L = R·I·(π/180)` |\n| Stationing | `PC = PI − T`,  `PT = PC + L` |\n| Vertical curve elevation | `Y = Y_PVC + g₁·x + [(g₂−g₁)/(2L)]·x²` |\n| Turning point from PVC | `x = −g₁·L/(g₂ − g₁)` |\n\n### Photogrammetry & mapping\n| Quantity | Formula |\n|---|---|\n| Photo scale | `S = f / (H − h)` |\n| Ground sample distance | `GSD = (pixel size · H) / f` |\n| Relief displacement | `d = r·h / H` |\n\n### Geodesy & state plane\n| Quantity | Formula |\n|---|---|\n| Geoid relationship | `H = h − N` |\n| Elevation factor | `EF = R/(R + h)` (R ≈ 20,906,000 ft) |\n| Combined factor | `CF = SF · EF` |\n| Grid ↔ ground | `grid = ground · CF`;  `ground = grid / CF` |\n\n### Business & economics\n| Quantity | Formula |\n|---|---|\n| Single-payment future worth | `F = P·(1 + i)ⁿ` |\n| Straight-line depreciation | `D = (C − S)/n` |\n| Risk | `Risk = Hazard × Probability` |"},{"type":"examples","title":"Worked Examples","content":"## Mixed exam-style problems (each combines topics)\n\nThese mirror how the FS chains concepts. Calculator keys are for the **TI-36X Pro / Casio fx-991** (with **HP-35S** RPN noted). Set **DEGREE mode** first.\n\n### A closed four-sided traverse\n\nThe figure shows the loop traverse used in Example 1: four legs by azimuth and distance returning to the start.\n\n<svg width=\"460\" height=\"360\" viewBox=\"0 0 460 360\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" style=\"background:#fff;border:1px solid #ccc\">\n  <polygon points=\"120,300 370,155 250,55 0,200\" fill=\"#eef4fb\" stroke=\"#1c4e80\" stroke-width=\"2\" transform=\"translate(40,10)\"/>\n  <g transform=\"translate(40,10)\">\n    <circle cx=\"120\" cy=\"300\" r=\"4\" fill=\"#c0392b\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"370\" cy=\"155\" r=\"4\" fill=\"#c0392b\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"250\" cy=\"55\" r=\"4\" fill=\"#c0392b\"/>\n    <circle cx=\"0\" cy=\"200\" r=\"4\" fill=\"#c0392b\"/>\n    <text x=\"98\" y=\"320\" font-size=\"14\" font-weight=\"bold\">A</text>\n    <text x=\"378\" y=\"153\" font-size=\"14\" font-weight=\"bold\">B</text>\n    <text x=\"256\" y=\"48\" font-size=\"14\" font-weight=\"bold\">C</text>\n    <text x=\"-14\" y=\"200\" font-size=\"14\" font-weight=\"bold\">D</text>\n    <text x=\"235\" y=\"240\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#1c4e80\">AB: Az 30°, 500.00 ft</text>\n    <text x=\"300\" y=\"110\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#1c4e80\">BC: Az 120°, 300.00 ft</text>\n    <text x=\"95\" y=\"110\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#1c4e80\">CD: Az 210°, 500.00 ft</text>\n    <text x=\"5\" y=\"265\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#1c4e80\">DA: Az 300°, 299.85 ft</text>\n  </g>\n</svg>\n\n---\n\n### Example 1 — Traverse → misclosure → relative precision → area (multi-step)\n\nA four-leg closed loop A→B→C→D→A has azimuths/distances: **AB Az 30°00′, 500.00 ft; BC Az 120°00′, 300.00 ft; CD Az 210°00′, 500.00 ft; DA Az 300°00′, 299.85 ft.** Find the linear misclosure, the relative precision, and the enclosed area (acres) by coordinates. Start at A (N 5,000.00, E 5,000.00).\n\n**Step 1 — latitudes & departures** (Lat = L·cos Az, Dep = L·sin Az):\n\n| Leg | Az | L | Lat = L·cos Az | Dep = L·sin Az |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| AB | 30° | 500.00 | +433.013 | +250.000 |\n| BC | 120° | 300.00 | −150.000 | +259.808 |\n| CD | 210° | 500.00 | −433.013 | −250.000 |\n| DA | 300° | 299.85 | +149.925 | −259.678 |\n| **Σ** | | **1,599.85** | **−0.075** | **+0.130** |\n\n**Step 2 — linear misclosure:** `misclose = √(ΣLat² + ΣDep²) = √((−0.075)² + (0.130)²) = hypot(−0.075, 0.130) = 0.150 ft`.\n\n**Step 3 — relative precision:** `= misclose / perimeter = 0.150 / 1,599.85 = 1/10,666`, i.e. about **1:10,700** — well within a normal traverse standard.\n\n**Step 4 — coordinates** (running from A, before adjustment): B(N 5,433.01, E 5,250.00), C(N 5,283.01, E 5,509.81), D(N 4,850.00, E 5,259.81). **Step 5 — area by coordinates** (shoelace, X = E, Y = N) on the four corners gives **A ≈ 168,300 ft² ÷ 43,560 = 3.86 acres**.\n\n**Calculator:** for each leg use **P▸R** — enter L, swap, enter Az, convert; read departure (ΔE) and latitude (ΔN) directly, accumulating with M+. The misclosure is one **R▸P** on (ΣLat, ΣDep): distance = 0.150 ft.\n\n---\n\n### Example 2 — Inverse + bearing reduction\n\nFrom monument P (N 17,095.84, E 44,600.31) to monument Q (N 16,917.92, E 43,781.05), find the distance and azimuth.\n\n1. `ΔN = 16,917.92 − 17,095.84 = −177.92`;  `ΔE = 43,781.05 − 44,600.31 = −819.26`.\n2. **Distance:** `D = hypot(ΔN, ΔE) = √(177.92² + 819.26²) = 838.35 ft`.\n3. **Azimuth:** both ΔN and ΔE negative → Quadrant III (SW). `Az = atan2(ΔE, ΔN)` reduced to 0–360° = **257°45′** (bearing S 77°45′ W).\n\n**Calculator (R▸P):** enter ΔE, swap, enter ΔN, **R▸P** → distance; swap → angle; if negative add 360°, then **▸DMS**.\n\n---\n\n### Example 3 — Error propagation on a measured area\n\nA rectangular lot is measured **120.00 ± 0.04 ft** by **144.00 ± 0.05 ft**. State the area and its standard error.\n\n1. **Area** = 120.00 × 144.00 = **17,280 ft²**.\n2. **Propagate** (product rule): `σ_A = √[(L·σ_W)² + (W·σ_L)²] = √[(120·0.05)² + (144·0.04)²] = √(6.00² + 5.76²) = √(36.0 + 33.18) = √69.18 = ±8.3 ft²`.\n3. **Result:** **17,280 ± 8.3 ft²**.\n\n**Calculator:** `(120×.05)² ＋ (144×.04)²`, then `√`. This is the classic FS product-propagation item.\n\n---\n\n### Example 4 — Horizontal curve → stationing (multi-step)\n\nA curve has **R = 1,000.00 ft**, **I = 36°00′**, with **PI at station 80+00.00**. Find T, L, and the stations of PC and PT.\n\n1. **Tangent:** `T = R·tan(I/2) = 1,000·tan18° = 324.92 ft`.\n2. **Length:** `L = R·I·(π/180) = 1,000·toRad(36°) = 628.32 ft`.\n3. **PC = PI − T** = 8,000 − 324.92 = 7,675.08 → **station 76+75.08**.\n4. **PT = PC + L** = 7,675.08 + 628.32 = 8,303.40 → **station 83+03.40** (add the **arc**, not T).\n\n**Calculator:** `1000 × tan(18) =` → 324.92; `1000 × 36 × π ÷ 180 =` → 628.32. Sketch PI–PC–PT first so you never add T twice.\n\n---\n\n### Example 5 — Leveling + curvature/refraction\n\nA backsight on BM-A (Elev 845.32 ft) reads **BS = 4.55 ft**; a foresight to TP-1 reads **FS = 6.78 ft**.\n\n1. **HI** = Elev + BS = 845.32 + 4.55 = **849.87 ft**.\n2. **Elev TP-1** = HI − FS = 849.87 − 6.78 = **843.09 ft**.\n3. If the foresight were a long 0.30-mile shot (D = 1.58 thousand ft), the **(c & r)** correction ≈ 0.0206·D² = 0.0206·(1.58)² = **0.051 ft** (the rod reads high; subtract from the FS, raising the computed elevation).\n\n**Calculator:** straight add/subtract; for (c & r), `0.0206 × 1.58² =`.\n\n---\n\n### Example 6 — Photo scale + grid-to-ground (mixed mapping/geodesy)\n\nA vertical aerial photo is taken at flying height **H = 6,000 ft** above datum with a **152.4 mm (6 in) focal length** camera over terrain at **h = 1,200 ft**. A road measures **2.10 in** on the photo. (a) Find the photo scale; (b) the ground length; (c) if that ground length must be placed on the state-plane grid where **CF = 0.9999087**, find the grid length.\n\n1. **Scale:** `S = f/(H − h) = 0.5 ft/(6,000 − 1,200) = 1/9,600`.\n2. **Ground length:** photo 2.10 in × 9,600 = 20,160 in = **1,680.0 ft**.\n3. **Grid length:** `grid = ground · CF = 1,680.0 × 0.9999087 = 1,679.85 ft`.\n\n**Calculator:** scale denom `(6000−1200) ÷ 0.5 =` → 9,600; ground `2.10 × 9600 ÷ 12 =` → 1,680 ft; grid `× 0.9999087`."},{"type":"tips","title":"Exam Tips & Calculator Strategy","content":"## Final two-week study plan\n\n**Week 1 — shore up the heavy areas.**\n- **Days 1–2 — Boundary Law (Area 3, the largest).** Drill the **dignity of calls**, senior/junior rights, simultaneous-vs-sequential proration, PLSS restoration, easements, adverse possession, water boundaries. These are fast points — read, don''t compute.\n- **Days 3–4 — Computations (Area 5).** Re-run traverse closure/adjustment, area by coordinates, both curve families, leveling, volumes. Do them on your real calculator until conversions are reflexive.\n- **Day 5 — Math & stats (Area 7).** Error propagation, std error of mean, weights, normal-curve probabilities.\n- **Days 6–7 — Take the full mock once, untimed, open-handbook.** Find your weak categories from the result.\n\n**Week 2 — simulate and polish.**\n- **Days 8–9 — Processes & Principles/Geodesy (Areas 1 & 4).** GNSS/OPUS, control, H = h − N, datums, Lambert vs TM, convergence.\n- **Day 10 — Mapping & Photogrammetry (Area 2).** Photo scale, GSD, relief displacement, vector/raster, contours, map types.\n- **Day 11 — Business & Ethics (Area 6).** Canons, responsible charge, contracts, E&O, safety, simple economics — light reading.\n- **Day 12 — Take the full mock TIMED and closed-book** (handbook only). Review every miss.\n- **Day 13 — Targeted review** of remaining weak categories; redo only missed problem types.\n- **Day 14 (day before) — Light only.** Skim the formula sheet, confirm logistics, sleep.\n\n## Exam-day logistics\n\n- **Arrive early** at the Pearson VUE center with the required government **photo ID**; know the route (scope it the day before if you can).\n- Bring an **approved calculator** (TI-30X/36X, Casio fx-115/991, or HP 33s/35s) **with fresh batteries** — and ideally a backup of the same model. No programmable/graphing/CAS.\n- The center supplies scratch material; **no personal references** — the handbook and standards are on screen.\n- Eat beforehand; use the **25-min scheduled break** to reset. Earplugs/headphones are usually available.\n\n## Time budget & test-taking mindset\n\n- **~2.9 minutes per question** (110 in 5 h 20 m). Most boundary/ethics/definition items take well under a minute — **bank those first**.\n- **Preview, then triage:** answer the quick recall items, **flag and skip** long COGO/curve problems, return to them with the time you banked.\n- **Each question tests only 1–2 concepts** — don''t over-build. Use the simplest method (don''t run a traverse routine to area a rectangle).\n- **Eliminate** obviously wrong choices; **sanity-check with coordinate sense** (if a point can''t be SW of a known point, rule it out).\n- **Use the handbook as confirmation, not discovery** — know *where* each formula lives so you search, not hunt.\n- **Use all the time.** Reserve the last block to revisit every flagged item; never leave a question blank (no penalty for guessing).\n\n## Final checklist\n\n<ul><li>Approved calculator + backup, fresh batteries, DEGREE mode habit</li><li>Government photo ID matching your registration</li><li>Know the seven areas and that boundary + computations dominate</li><li>Reflexive on DMS↔decimal, R▸P / P▸R, statistics mode, store/recall</li><li>Master formula sheet internalized; handbook navigation practiced</li><li>At least one full timed, closed-book mock completed and reviewed</li><li>Logistics confirmed; rested</li></ul>\n\n## How the handbook helps\n\nEvery formula on the master sheet is in the NCEES FS Reference Handbook v2.x — trig, triangles, **horizontal and vertical curves, photogrammetry, geodesy, EDM, area formulas, earthwork, probability & statistics**, plus economics and the ethics canons. Practice pulling each up by name so that on exam day the formula is a one-look confirmation and your minutes go to setting up the problem, not recalling the equation."}]'::jsonb, 9, 70, 36, '🏁', 1000, true, 'approved')
ON CONFLICT (module_number) DO UPDATE SET title=EXCLUDED.title, description=EXCLUDED.description, week_range=EXCLUDED.week_range, exam_weight_percent=EXCLUDED.exam_weight_percent, key_topics=EXCLUDED.key_topics, key_formulas=EXCLUDED.key_formulas, content_sections=EXCLUDED.content_sections, prerequisite_module=EXCLUDED.prerequisite_module, question_count=EXCLUDED.question_count, icon=EXCLUDED.icon, xp_reward=EXCLUDED.xp_reward, is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now();
  'fb105000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', 'Standard error of the mean', 'Standard error of the mean', 'FS — Applied Mathematics and Statistics', 'Error Analysis', 'numeric_input', 'easy', 'A distance is measured {{n}} times. The standard deviation of a single measurement is σ = {{sigma:f3}} ft. Compute the standard error of the mean (ft).', 'sigma/sqrt(n)', '{"decimals":4,"unit":"ft","tolerance":0.0005}', '[{"name":"n","type":"integer","min":4,"max":25},{"name":"sigma","type":"float","min":0.02,"max":0.2,"decimals":3}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Standard error of mean","formula":"σ_m = σ/√n","calculation_template":"{{sigma:f3}} / √{{n}}"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Result","result_template":"σ_m = {{_answer}} ft"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'The standard error of the mean improves with the square root of the number of observations: σ_m = σ/√n = {{sigma:f3}}/√{{n}} = {{_answer}} ft.', 'f500000a-0000-0000-0000-00000000000a', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m10','fs-practice']::text[], NULL, true, 'fs:m10');
  'fb105000-0000-0000-0000-000000000002', 'Inverse distance between two points', 'Inverse distance between two points', 'FS — Plane Survey Computations', 'COGO', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'Point A is at (N {{nA:f2}}, E {{eA:f2}}). Point B is at (N {{nB:f2}}, E {{eB:f2}}). Compute the horizontal distance A→B (ft).', 'hypot(dN,dE)', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"ft","tolerance":0.1}', '[{"name":"nA","type":"float","min":1000,"max":5000,"decimals":2},{"name":"eA","type":"float","min":1000,"max":5000,"decimals":2},{"name":"dN","type":"float","min":-1500,"max":1500,"decimals":2},{"name":"dE","type":"float","min":-1500,"max":1500,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"nB","formula":"nA+dN"},{"name":"eB","formula":"eA+dE"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Latitude & departure","calculation_template":"ΔN = {{dN:f2}}, ΔE = {{dE:f2}}"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Distance = √(ΔN²+ΔE²)","result_template":"{{_answer}} ft (calc: R▸P)"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Use rectangular→polar: enter ΔN and ΔE; the calculator returns distance = hypot(ΔN, ΔE) = {{_answer}} ft directly.', 'f500000a-0000-0000-0000-00000000000a', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m10','fs-practice']::text[], NULL, true, 'fs:m10');
  'fb105000-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', 'Inverse azimuth between two points', 'Inverse azimuth between two points', 'FS — Plane Survey Computations', 'COGO', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'From point A (N {{nA:f2}}, E {{eA:f2}}) to point B (N {{nB:f2}}, E {{eB:f2}}), compute the azimuth of line A→B (decimal degrees, 0–360°).', '(toDeg(atan2(dE,dN))+360)%360', '{"decimals":3,"unit":"°","tolerance":0.02}', '[{"name":"nA","type":"float","min":1000,"max":5000,"decimals":2},{"name":"eA","type":"float","min":1000,"max":5000,"decimals":2},{"name":"dN","type":"float","min":-1500,"max":1500,"decimals":2},{"name":"dE","type":"float","min":-1500,"max":1500,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"nB","formula":"nA+dN"},{"name":"eB","formula":"eA+dE"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Components","calculation_template":"ΔN = {{dN:f2}}, ΔE = {{dE:f2}}"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Azimuth = atan2(ΔE, ΔN), reduced to 0–360°","result_template":"{{_answer}}°"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Azimuth = atan2(ΔE, ΔN); add 360° if negative so the result lies in 0–360°. Here Az = {{_answer}}°. The signs of ΔN and ΔE place it in the correct quadrant automatically.', 'f500000a-0000-0000-0000-00000000000a', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m10','fs-practice']::text[], NULL, true, 'fs:m10');
  'fb105000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'Forward coordinates from azimuth and distance', 'Forward coordinates from azimuth and distance', 'FS — Plane Survey Computations', 'COGO', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'From point P (N {{nP:f2}}, E {{eP:f2}}), a line runs azimuth {{az:f2}}° for a distance of {{dist:f2}} ft to point Q. Compute the NORTHING of point Q (ft).', 'nP + dist*cos(toRad(az))', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"ft","tolerance":0.05}', '[{"name":"nP","type":"float","min":1000,"max":5000,"decimals":2},{"name":"eP","type":"float","min":1000,"max":5000,"decimals":2},{"name":"az","type":"float","min":0,"max":359,"decimals":2},{"name":"dist","type":"float","min":100,"max":1200,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Latitude = L·cos(Az)","calculation_template":"ΔN = {{dist:f2}}·cos({{az:f2}}°)"},{"step_number":2,"title":"New northing","formula":"N_Q = N_P + ΔN","result_template":"{{_answer}} ft"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'The latitude is ΔN = L·cos(Az), so N_Q = N_P + L·cos(Az) = {{nP:f2}} + {{dist:f2}}·cos({{az:f2}}°) = {{_answer}} ft (calc: P▸R, read the latitude component).', 'f500000a-0000-0000-0000-00000000000a', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m10','fs-practice']::text[], NULL, true, 'fs:m10');
  'fb105000-0000-0000-0000-000000000005', 'Area by coordinates (quadrilateral) → acres', 'Area by coordinates (quadrilateral) → acres', 'FS — Plane Survey Computations', 'Area', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'A four-corner parcel has corners, in order, A (N {{nA:f2}}, E {{eA:f2}}), B (N {{nB:f2}}, E {{eB:f2}}), C (N {{nC:f2}}, E {{eC:f2}}), and D (N {{nD:f2}}, E {{eD:f2}}). Compute the enclosed area by coordinates (shoelace) and report it in ACRES.', 'abs((eA*nB-eB*nA)+(eB*nC-eC*nB)+(eC*nD-eD*nC)+(eD*nA-eA*nD))/2/43560', '{"decimals":3,"unit":"acres","tolerance":0.01}', '[{"name":"nA","type":"float","min":1000,"max":1100,"decimals":2},{"name":"eA","type":"float","min":1000,"max":1100,"decimals":2},{"name":"w","type":"float","min":300,"max":700,"decimals":2},{"name":"h","type":"float","min":300,"max":700,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"eB","formula":"eA+w"},{"name":"nB","formula":"nA"},{"name":"eC","formula":"eA+w"},{"name":"nC","formula":"nA+h"},{"name":"eD","formula":"eA"},{"name":"nD","formula":"nA+h"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Use X = Easting, Y = Northing","calculation_template":"A({{eA:f2}},{{nA:f2}}), B({{eB:f2}},{{nB:f2}}), C({{eC:f2}},{{nC:f2}}), D({{eD:f2}},{{nD:f2}})"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Shoelace sum, halved, absolute value","formula":"A = ½|Σ(Xᵢ·Y_{i+1} − X_{i+1}·Yᵢ)|","calculation_template":"Sum the four cross-products, halve the absolute value → ft²"},{"step_number":3,"title":"Convert to acres","result_template":"{{_answer}} acres (= ft² ÷ 43,560)"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Apply the shoelace formula with X = Easting, Y = Northing, vertices in order A→B→C→D, take the absolute value, then divide by 43,560 ft²/acre. Area = {{_answer}} acres.', 'f500000a-0000-0000-0000-00000000000a', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m10','fs-practice']::text[], NULL, true, 'fs:m10');
  'fb105000-0000-0000-0000-000000000006', 'Horizontal curve tangent distance T', 'Horizontal curve tangent distance T', 'FS — Plane Survey Computations', 'Horizontal Curves', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'A simple circular curve has radius R = {{R:f2}} ft and deflection (central) angle I = {{I:f2}}°. Compute the tangent distance T (ft).', 'R*tan(toRad(I/2))', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"ft","tolerance":0.1}', '[{"name":"R","type":"float","min":400,"max":2000,"decimals":2},{"name":"I","type":"float","min":8,"max":75,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Tangent = R·tan(I/2)","formula":"T = R·tan(I/2)","calculation_template":"{{R:f2}}·tan({{I:f2}}°/2)"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Result","result_template":"T = {{_answer}} ft"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'The tangent distance from the PI to the PC (and to the PT) is T = R·tan(I/2) = {{R:f2}}·tan({{I:f2}}°/2) = {{_answer}} ft. Set the calculator to DEGREE mode and use I/2.', 'f500000a-0000-0000-0000-00000000000a', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m10','fs-practice']::text[], NULL, true, 'fs:m10');
  'fb105000-0000-0000-0000-000000000007', 'Horizontal curve length L', 'Horizontal curve length L', 'FS — Plane Survey Computations', 'Horizontal Curves', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'A circular curve has radius R = {{R:f2}} ft and deflection angle I = {{I:f2}}°. Compute the curve (arc) length L (ft).', 'R*toRad(I)', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"ft","tolerance":0.1}', '[{"name":"R","type":"float","min":400,"max":2000,"decimals":2},{"name":"I","type":"float","min":8,"max":75,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Length = R·I (radians)","formula":"L = R·I·(π/180)","calculation_template":"{{R:f2}}·({{I:f2}}°·π/180)"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Result","result_template":"L = {{_answer}} ft"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'The arc length is L = R·I·(π/180) = {{R:f2}}·toRad({{I:f2}}°) = {{_answer}} ft. The PT is set by adding this arc length (not T) to the PC.', 'f500000a-0000-0000-0000-00000000000a', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m10','fs-practice']::text[], NULL, true, 'fs:m10');
  'fb105000-0000-0000-0000-000000000008', 'Differential leveling — new elevation', 'Differential leveling — new elevation', 'FS — Plane Survey Computations', 'Leveling', 'numeric_input', 'easy', 'A backsight of {{bs:f2}} ft is taken on a benchmark at elevation {{elev:f2}} ft, then a foresight of {{fs:f2}} ft is read to a turning point. Compute the elevation of the turning point (ft).', 'elev + bs - fs', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"ft","tolerance":0.01}', '[{"name":"elev","type":"float","min":100,"max":2000,"decimals":2},{"name":"bs","type":"float","min":0.5,"max":12,"decimals":2},{"name":"fs","type":"float","min":0.5,"max":12,"decimals":2}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"hi","formula":"elev+bs"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Height of instrument","formula":"HI = Elev + BS","calculation_template":"{{elev:f2}} + {{bs:f2}} = {{hi:f2}}"},{"step_number":2,"title":"New elevation","formula":"Elev = HI − FS","result_template":"{{_answer}} ft"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'HI = Elev + BS = {{elev:f2}} + {{bs:f2}} = {{hi:f2}} ft; then Elev = HI − FS = {{hi:f2}} − {{fs:f2}} = {{_answer}} ft.', 'f500000a-0000-0000-0000-00000000000a', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m10','fs-practice']::text[], NULL, true, 'fs:m10');
  'fb105000-0000-0000-0000-000000000009', 'Vertical photo scale denominator', 'Vertical photo scale denominator', 'FS — Mapping and Photogrammetry', 'Photogrammetry', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'A vertical aerial photo is taken at flying height H = {{H:f1}} ft above datum with a focal length f = {{f:f3}} ft, over terrain at average ground height h = {{h:f1}} ft. Compute the scale denominator (the number S in 1:S).', '(H-h)/f', '{"decimals":0,"unit":"","tolerance":5}', '[{"name":"H","type":"float","min":4000,"max":12000,"decimals":1},{"name":"f","type":"float","min":0.3,"max":1,"decimals":3},{"name":"h","type":"float","min":200,"max":2000,"decimals":1}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Photo scale","formula":"S = f/(H − h)","calculation_template":"scale = {{f:f3}} / ({{H:f1}} − {{h:f1}})"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Scale denominator","result_template":"1 : {{_answer}}"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Photo scale S = f/(H − h); the denominator is (H − h)/f = ({{H:f1}} − {{h:f1}})/{{f:f3}} = {{_answer}}, i.e. a scale of 1:{{_answer}}.', 'f500000a-0000-0000-0000-00000000000a', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m10','fs-practice']::text[], NULL, true, 'fs:m10');
  'fb105000-0000-0000-0000-000000000010', 'Grid distance from ground (combined factor)', 'Grid distance from ground (combined factor)', 'FS — Surveying Principles', 'State Plane', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'A ground distance of {{ground:f2}} ft is to be reduced to the state-plane grid using a combined factor CF = {{cf:f7}}. Compute the grid distance (ft).', 'ground*cf', '{"decimals":2,"unit":"ft","tolerance":0.05}', '[{"name":"ground","type":"float","min":1000,"max":8000,"decimals":2},{"name":"cf","type":"float","min":0.9998,"max":1.00015,"decimals":7}]'::jsonb, '[]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Grid = ground × combined factor","formula":"grid = ground · CF","calculation_template":"{{ground:f2}} × {{cf:f7}}"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Result","result_template":"{{_answer}} ft"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'To go from ground to grid, multiply by the combined factor (CF = scale factor × elevation factor): grid = {{ground:f2}} × {{cf:f7}} = {{_answer}} ft. (To reverse, divide grid by CF.)', 'f500000a-0000-0000-0000-00000000000a', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m10','fs-practice']::text[], NULL, true, 'fs:m10');
  'fb105000-0000-0000-0000-000000000011', 'Average-end-area volume → cubic yards', 'Average-end-area volume → cubic yards', 'FS — Plane Survey Computations', 'Volume', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'Two adjacent cross-sections {{L:f1}} ft apart have end areas A₁ = {{a1:f1}} ft² and A₂ = {{a2:f1}} ft². Using the average-end-area method, compute the earthwork volume in CUBIC YARDS.', 'L*(a1+a2)/2/27', '{"decimals":1,"unit":"yd³","tolerance":0.5}', '[{"name":"L","type":"float","min":50,"max":150,"decimals":1},{"name":"a1","type":"float","min":60,"max":300,"decimals":1},{"name":"a2","type":"float","min":60,"max":300,"decimals":1}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"vft3","formula":"L*(a1+a2)/2"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Average end area","formula":"V = L·(A₁+A₂)/2","calculation_template":"{{L:f1}}·({{a1:f1}}+{{a2:f1}})/2 = {{vft3:f1}} ft³"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Convert to cubic yards (÷27)","result_template":"{{_answer}} yd³"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Average end area: V = L·(A₁+A₂)/2 = {{L:f1}}·({{a1:f1}}+{{a2:f1}})/2 = {{vft3:f1}} ft³. Divide by 27 ft³/yd³ → {{_answer}} yd³.', 'f500000a-0000-0000-0000-00000000000a', 'FS', ARRAY['fs-buildout','fs-m10','fs-practice']::text[], NULL, true, 'fs:m10');

COMMIT;
SELECT 'FS prep: ' || (SELECT count(*) FROM fs_study_modules) || ' modules, ' || (SELECT count(*) FROM question_bank WHERE 'fs-buildout'=ANY(tags) AND exam_category='FS') || ' FS questions, ' || (SELECT count(*) FROM question_bank WHERE exam_category='FS-MOCK' AND 'fs-buildout'=ANY(tags)) || ' mock questions.' AS status;